{"title_page": "War of the Heavenly Horses", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=War of the Heavenly Horses\n|partof=\n|image=File:Han Expansion.png\n|caption=\n|date= 104\u2013101 BC\n|place= [[Ferghana Valley]]\n|result= Han victory\n*Dayuan becomes a puppet-state of Han\n*Han gets 3,000 horses to begin building its cavalry force\n*Yucheng conquered and royal family executed\n*Establishment of [[Protectorate of the Western Regions]] \n|territory=\n|combatant1= [[Han dynasty]]\n|combatant2= {{Plainlist|\n* [[Dayuan]]\n* [[Uzgen|Yucheng]]\n* [[Luntai]]}}\n|commander1= {{Plainlist|\n* [[Li Guangli]]\n* [[Shangguan Jie]]\n* Wang Shensheng\n* Hu Chongguo}}\n|commander2= Wugua<br>Jianmi\n|strength1='''1st (104 BC)''':<br> 20,000 infantry<br>6,000 cavalry<br>'''2nd (102 BC)''':<br>60,000 infantry<br>30,000 cavalry<br>100,000 oxen<br>20,000 donkeys and camels\n|strength2={{Plainlist|\n* '''Dayuan''': ?\n* '''Yucheng''': 3,000\n* '''Luntai''': ?}}\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Han Campaigns and Battles}}\n[[File:UrumqiWarrior.jpg|thumb|The [[Sampul tapestry]], a woolen wall hanging from [[Lop County]], [[Hotan Prefecture]], [[Xinjiang]], [[China]], showing a possibly [[Hellenistic civilization|Greek soldier]] from the [[Greco-Bactrian kingdom]] (250\u2013125 BC), with [[blue eyes]], wielding a spear, and wearing what appears to be a ''[[diadem]]'' headband; depicted above him is a [[centaur]], from [[Greek mythology]], a common [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]] in [[Hellenistic art]]]]\n\nThe '''War of the Heavenly Horses''' or the '''Han\u2013Dayuan war''' was a military conflict fought in 104 BC and 102 BC between the [[China|Chinese]] [[Han dynasty]] and the [[Greeks|Greek]] kingdom known to the Chinese as [[Dayuan]], in [[Central Asia]] at the easternmost end of the old [[Persia]]n empire, around what is now [[Uzbekistan]]. Dayuan was a Chinese [[exonym]] for the area, meaning \"Great [[Ionians|Ionian]]\"). The result was Han victory, and a temporary expansion of its [[hegemony]] deep into central Asia.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/china-watch/culture/tianma-chinas-heavenly-horses/|title=Why were China's horses of the ancient Silk Road so heavenly?|date=2019-04-26|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-04-27|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/empires-of-ancient-eurasia/zhang-qian-and-han-expansion-into-central-asia/B9352627ADD0B8E5FCB3EA13C7DF7B04|title=Zhang Qian and Han Expansion into Central Asia|last=Benjamin|first=Craig|date=May 2018|website=Empires of Ancient Eurasia: The First Silk Roads Era, 100 BCE \u2013 250 CE|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>\n\n[[Emperor Wu of Han]] had received reports from diplomat [[Zhang Qian]] that Dayuan owned tall and powerful horses (\"[[Ferghana horse|heavenly horses]]\") that could help fight against the [[Xiongnu]]. He sent Zhang Qian to survey the region and purchase horses. Dayuan refused the deal, resulting in the death of one of the Han ambassadors, and confiscated the gold sent as payment. So the Han sent an army to capture [[Alexandria Eschate]] of \"Dayuan\", at the time one of the easternmost points of the [[Hellenistic world|Hellenistic World]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sutori.com/item/104-bce-the-war-of-the-heavenly-horses-general-li-guangli-forces-the-city-of-da|title=Sutori|website=www.sutori.com|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>\n\nTheir first incursion failed, but the second, larger force defeated Dayuan, installed a regime favorable to the Han, and won enough horses to later build a cavalry strong enough to defeat the Xiongnu in the [[Han\u2013Xiongnu War]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Background==\n\n=== The horses ===\nAccording to author Zhao Xu, compared to the Trojan horse which embodied \"military subterfuge\" the heavenly horses of Dayuan ([[Ferghana horse]]s or \u5929\u9a6c) embodied \"raw speed and stamina\", the perfect breed of war horses.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEmperor Wudi wanted to raise an \"invincible cavalry\" to defeat the nomadic steppe [[Xiongnu]], who had historically harassed the Han dynasty for decades before. So in 139 BC he sent an envoy by the name of [[Zhang Qian]] west to search for the heavenly horses of Dayuan as well as forge military alliances with tribes like the [[Yuezhi]] against the Xiongnu.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn the way to Central Asia through the [[Gobi Desert|Gobi desert]], Zhang was captured twice. According to \"''Houhanshu'' (the ''Book of the Later Han'', penned by a Chinese historian during the fifth century and considered an authoritative record of the Han history between 25 and 220), about 10, or at least five or six, diplomatic groups were dispatched annually by the Han court to Central Asia during this period to buy horses.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe horses have since captured the popular imagination of China, leading to horse carvings, breeding grounds in [[Gansu]], and up to 430,000 such horses in the cavalry during even the [[Tang dynasty]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Xiongnu ===\nFor decades prior the Han followed a policy of ''[[heqin]]'' (\u548c\u4eb2) sending tribute and princesses to marry the Xiongnu ''shanyu'' to maintain peace. This changed when Emperor Wudi came into power, when the Han adopted and revived a policy to defeat the Xiongnu.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Dayuan ===\n\n''[[Records of the Grand Historian]]'' and the ''[[Book of Han]]'' describe the [[Dayuan]] as urbanized dwellers living in walled cities and having \"customs identical to those of the [[Greco-Bactrians]]\", a [[Hellenistic civilization|Hellenistic]] kingdom that was ruling [[Bactria]] at that time in today's [[Tajikistan]]. The Dayuan are also described as manufacturers and great lovers of wine.{{sfn|Watson|1993|pp=244\u201345}}\n\nDayuan was among one of the furthest western states to send envoys to the Han court. However unlike the other envoys, the ones from Dayuan did not conform to the proper Han rituals and behaved with great arrogance and self-assurance, believing they were too far away to be in any danger of invasion. Dayuan was also situated near the Xiongnu at this point, who were held in great respect for they had caused the [[Yuezhi]] much suffering. An envoy from the Xiongnu bearing the credentials of the [[Chanyu]] was provided with food and escort. In comparison, a Han envoy received no mounts he did not buy himself and no food unless he handed out silks and other goods. Han envoys also had a reputation for wealth in the west, thus they were charged exorbitant fees wherever they went, causing the Han no small amount of grief.{{sfn|Watson|1993|p=244}} However the historian [[Sima Qian]] provides a different account:\n\n{{quotation|The envoys were all sons of poor families who handled the government gifts and goods that were entrusted to them as though they were private property and looked for opportunities to buy goods at a cheap price in the foreign countries and make a profit on their return to China. The men of the foreign lands soon became disgusted when they found that each of the Han envoys told some different story and, considering that the Han armies were too far away to worry about, refused to supply the envoys with food and provisions, making things very difficult for them. The Han envoys were soon reduced to a state of destitution and distress and, their tempers mounting, fell to quarrelling and even attacking each other.{{sfn|Watson|1993|p=242}}|''[[Shiji]]''}}\n\nAmong the goods western envoys brought with them were the \"heavenly horses\", which the emperor took a liking to. He sent a trade mission with 1,000 pieces of gold and a golden horse to purchase these horses from Dayuan. Dayuan had at this point already been trading with the Han for quite some time and benefited greatly from it. Not only were they overflowing with eastern goods, they also learned from Han soldiers how to cast metal into coins and weapons. Thus they had no great reason to accept the Han trade offer, reasoning:\n\n{{quotation|The Han is far away from us and on several occasions has lost men in the salt-water wastes between our country and China. Yet if the Han parties go farther north, they will be harassed by the Xiongnu, while if they try to go south they will suffer from lack of water and fodder. Moreover, there are many places along the route where there are no cities whatsoever and they are apt to run out of provisions. The Han embassies that have come to us are made up of only a few hundred men, and yet they are always short of food and over half the men die on the journey. Under such circumstances how could the Han possibly send a large army against us? What have we to worry about? Furthermore, the horses of Ershi are one of the most valuable treasures of the state!{{sfn|Watson|1993|p=246}}|[[Dayuan]], ''[[Shiji]]''}}\n\nThe Han envoys cursed the men of Dayuan and smashed the golden horse they had brought. Enraged by this act of contempt, the nobles of Dayuan ordered Yucheng (modern [[Uzgen]]), which lay on their eastern borders, to attack and kill the envoys and seize their goods. Upon receiving word of the trade mission's demise, Emperor Wu decided to dispatch a punitive expedition against Dayuan. [[Li Guangli]], brother of Emperor Wu's favorite concubine, [[Lady Li]], was appointed Ershi General and sent against Dayuan with 6,000 cavalry and 20,000 young men drawn from the undesirables among the border kingdoms.{{sfn|Watson|1993|p=246}}\n\n==First expedition (104 BC)==\nIn the autumn of 104 BC, Li Guangli set out with an army of 6,000 cavalry and 20,000 infantry. While crossing the [[Tarim Basin]] and the [[Taklamakan Desert]] (of modern [[Xinjiang]]), Li's army was forced to attack the nearby oasis states because they refused to provide them with supplies. Sometimes they were unable to overcome the oasis states. If the siege lasted for more than a few days, the army moved on without any supplies. Due to these numerous petty conflicts, the army became exhausted and was reduced to starvation after their supplies ran out. By the time they neared Dayuan, Li had already lost too much manpower to continue the campaign. After suffering a defeat at Yucheng, Li concluded that their current strength would not be sufficient to take the Dayuan capital, Ershi ([[Khujand]]), and therefore returned to [[Dunhuang]].{{sfn|Peers|1995|p=8}}\n\n==Second expedition (102 BC)==\nThe court officials wanted to disband Li's expeditionary army and concentrate their resources toward fighting the Xiongnu. Emperor Wu refused out of fear that failure to subdue Dayuan would result in a loss of prestige with the western states. He responded by giving Li a much larger army as well as supply animals. In the autumn of 102 BC, Li set out with an army of 60,000 recruits from the prison population and 30,000 horses along with a large number of supply animals including 100,000 oxen and 20,000 donkeys and camels. This time the expedition had no problem dealing with the oasis states.{{sfn|Peers|1995|p=8}}{{sfn|Whiting|2002|p=164}}\n\nMost of them simply surrendered without a fight upon seeing the overwhelming display of power. The only state that put up any resistance was [[Luntai]], for which Li had its populace massacred. Despite meeting no major setbacks and bypassing Yucheng entirely, Li still lost half his army by the time they reached Dayuan.{{sfn|Peers|1995|p=8}} Upon arriving at Ershi, Li immediately laid siege to it. A force of [[Wusun]] cavalry 2,000 strong was also present at the request of Emperor Wu, but they refused to take part in the siege out of fear of offending either parties. Dayuan's forces sallied out in an attempt to break the siege, but they were easily defeated by Han crossbowmen. Han engineers set to work on the river passing through Ershi and diverted it, leaving the city with no source of water as they had no wells. After a 40-day siege, the Han broke through the outer wall and captured the enemy general, Jianmi. The nobles of Ershi withdrew to the inner walls and decided to offer terms of surrender. First they killed their king, Wugua, and sent his head to Li. Then they offered Li all the horses he wanted as well as supplies in return for the army's withdrawal, but if he did not accept, they would kill all their horses. Li agreed to the terms, taking some 3,000 horses as well as provisions. Before departing, Li enthroned as king one of the nobles called Meicai (\u6627\u8521), since he had previously shown kindness to the Han envoys.{{sfn|Whiting|2002|p=165}}\n\nAs Li set out for Dunhuang, he realized that the local areas along the way would not be able to adequately supply the army. The army separated into several groups, some taking the northern route while others the southern route. One of these groups, comprising only 1,000 or so men under the command of [[Wang Shensheng]] and [[Hu Chongguo]], tried to take Yucheng. After several days under siege, the inhabitants of Yucheng sallied out with 3,000 men and defeated the besieging army. A few of the Han soldiers managed to escape and alert Li of the defeat. Thereupon, Li dispatched [[Shangguan Jie]] to attack Yucheng. Seeing the great host sent against him, the king of Yucheng decided to flee to [[Kangju]], causing Yucheng to surrender shortly thereafter. When Kangju received news of Dayuan's defeat, they handed the king of Yucheng over to Shangguan, who had him executed.{{sfn|Whiting|2002|p=165}}\n\nThe army met no further opposition on the way back to [[Yumen Pass]]. Having heard of Dayuan's defeat, the rulers of the oasis states sent their kin along with the army back to the Han capital, where they presented tribute to Emperor Wu. They remained at the Han court as hostages. Despite the overall success of the second expedition, having adequate supplies and losing only a small portion of the army in battle, the entire campaign was marred by corruption and self interest. Li's soldiers, being taken from the prison population and undesirable class, were given very little care by their generals and officers, who instead abused them by withholding rations, causing desertion. As a result, Li returned with just 10,000 men and 1,000 horses fit for military service. Even so, Emperor Wu still considered these to be acceptable losses in the victory over Dayuan, and made no attempts to punish those who were responsible. Those who had survived were given handsome rewards. Li Guangli was enfeoffed as Marquis of [[Haixi Mongol and Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture|Haixi]]. [[Zhao Di]], who secured the capture of the king of Yucheng, became Marquis of [[Xinzhi]]. Shangguan Jie became privy treasurer.{{sfn|Whiting|2002|p=165}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nMore than a year later, the nobles of Dayuan banded together and killed King Meicai, who they considered responsible for the entire affair with the Han in the first place. Wugua's brother, Chanfeng, became the new king. Not wishing to upset the Han, Chanfeng sent his son as hostage to the Han court. In response, the Han dispatched envoys with gifts for the new ruler and made peace with Dayuan.{{sfn|Watson|1993|p=252}}\n\nTen years later, Li Guangli was defeated by the Xiongnu and defected to their side. He married the [[Chanyu]]'s daughter but was eventually executed over a conflict with another Han defector more favored by the Chanyu.<ref>{{cite book |author=Lin Jianming (\u6797\u5251\u9e23) |title=\u79e6\u6f22\u53f2 |trans-title=History of Qin and Han |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lqfrEY8UW1UC&pg=PA557 |year=1992 |publisher=Wunan Publishing |isbn=978-957-11-0574-1 |pages=557\u2013578}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*{{citation|last=Peers|first=C. J.|year=1995|title=Imperial Chinese Armies (1): 200 BC \u2013 AD 589|publisher=Osprey Publishing}}\n*{{citation|last=Watson|first=Burton|year=1993|title=Records of the Grand Historian by Sima Qian: Han Dynasty II (Revised Edition|publisher=Columbia University Press}} \n*{{citation|last=Whiting|first=Marvin C.|year=2002|title=Imperial Chinese Military History|publisher=Writers Club Press}}\n\n{{Han dynasty topics}}\n\n[[Category:100s BC conflicts]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Han dynasty]]\n[[Category:Wars of the Hellenistic period]]\n[[Category:Military history of Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:2nd century BC in China]]\n[[Category:Horse in Chinese mythology]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=War of the Heavenly Horses\n|partof=\n|image=File:Han Expansion.png\n|caption=\n|date= 104\u2013101 BC\n|place= [[Ferghana Valley]]\n|result= Han victory\n*Dayuan becomes a puppet-state of Han\n*Han gets 3,000 horses to begin building its cavalry force\n*Yucheng conquered and royal family executed\n*Establishment of [[Protectorate of the Western Regions]] \n|territory=\n|combatant1= [[Han dynasty]]\n|combatant2= {{Plainlist|\n* [[Dayuan]]\n* [[Uzgen|Yucheng]]\n* [[Luntai]]}}\n|commander1= {{Plainlist|\n* [[Li Guangli]]\n* [[Shangguan Jie]]\n* Wang Shensheng\n* Hu Chongguo}}\n|commander2= Wugua<br>Jianmi\n|strength1='''1st (104 BC)''':<br> 20,000 infantry<br>6,000 cavalry<br>'''2nd (102 BC)''':<br>60,000 infantry<br>30,000 cavalry<br>100,000 oxen<br>20,000 donkeys and camels\n|strength2={{Plainlist|\n* '''Dayuan''': ?\n* '''Yucheng''': 3,000\n* '''Luntai''': ?}}\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Han Campaigns and Battles}}\n[[File:UrumqiWarrior.jpg|thumb|The [[Sampul tapestry]], a woolen wall hanging from [[Lop County]], [[Hotan Prefecture]], [[Xinjiang]], [[China]], showing a possibly [[Hellenistic civilization|Greek soldier]] from the [[Greco-Bactrian kingdom]] (250\u2013125 BC), with [[blue eyes]], wielding a spear, and wearing what appears to be a ''[[diadem]]'' headband; depicted above him is a [[centaur]], from [[Greek mythology]], a common [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]] in [[Hellenistic art]]]]\n\nThe '''War of the Heavenly Horses''' or the '''Han\u2013Dayuan war''' was a military conflict fought in 104 BC and 102 BC between the [[China|Chinese]] [[Han dynasty]] and the [[Greeks|Greek]] kingdom of the Chinese referred to as Dayuan, in [[Central Asia]] at the easternmost end of the old [[Persia]]n empire, around what is now [[Uzbekistan]]. Dayuan was a Chinese [[exonym]] for the area, meaning \"Great [[Ionians|Ionian]]\"). The result was Han victory, and a temporary expansion of its [[hegemony]] deep into central Asia.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/china-watch/culture/tianma-chinas-heavenly-horses/|title=Why were China's horses of the ancient Silk Road so heavenly?|date=2019-04-26|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-04-27|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/empires-of-ancient-eurasia/zhang-qian-and-han-expansion-into-central-asia/B9352627ADD0B8E5FCB3EA13C7DF7B04|title=Zhang Qian and Han Expansion into Central Asia|last=Benjamin|first=Craig|date=May 2018|website=Empires of Ancient Eurasia: The First Silk Roads Era, 100 BCE \u2013 250 CE|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>\n\n[[Emperor Wu of Han]] had received reports from diplomat [[Zhang Qian]] that Dayuan owned tall and powerful horses (\"[[Ferghana horse|heavenly horses]]\") that could help fight against the [[Xiongnu]]. He sent Zhang Qian to survey the region and purchase horses. Dayuan refused the deal, resulting in the death of one of the Han ambassadors, and confiscated the gold sent as payment. So the Han sent an army to capture [[Alexandria Eschate]] of \"Dayuan\", at the time one of the easternmost points of the [[Hellenistic world|Hellenistic World]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sutori.com/item/104-bce-the-war-of-the-heavenly-horses-general-li-guangli-forces-the-city-of-da|title=Sutori|website=www.sutori.com|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>\n\nTheir first incursion failed, but the second, larger force defeated Dayuan, installed a regime favorable to the Han, and won enough horses to later build a cavalry strong enough to defeat the Xiongnu in the [[Han\u2013Xiongnu War]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Background==\n\n=== The horses ===\nAccording to author Zhao Xu, compared to the Trojan horse which embodied \"military subterfuge\" the heavenly horses of Dayuan ([[Ferghana horse]]s or \u5929\u9a6c) embodied \"raw speed and stamina\", the perfect breed of war horses.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEmperor Wudi wanted to raise an \"invincible cavalry\" to defeat the nomadic steppe [[Xiongnu]], who had historically harassed the Han dynasty for decades before. So in 139 BC he sent an envoy by the name of [[Zhang Qian]] west to search for the heavenly horses of Dayuan as well as forge military alliances with tribes like the [[Yuezhi]] against the Xiongnu.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn the way to Central Asia through the [[Gobi Desert|Gobi desert]], Zhang was captured twice. According to \"''Houhanshu'' (the ''Book of the Later Han'', penned by a Chinese historian during the fifth century and considered an authoritative record of the Han history between 25 and 220), about 10, or at least five or six, diplomatic groups were dispatched annually by the Han court to Central Asia during this period to buy horses.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe horses have since captured the popular imagination of China, leading to horse carvings, breeding grounds in [[Gansu]], and up to 430,000 such horses in the cavalry during even the [[Tang dynasty]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Xiongnu ===\nFor decades prior the Han followed a policy of ''[[heqin]]'' (\u548c\u4eb2) sending tribute and princesses to marry the Xiongnu ''shanyu'' to maintain peace. This changed when Emperor Wudi came into power, when the Han adopted and revived a policy to defeat the Xiongnu.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Dayuan ===\n\n''[[Records of the Grand Historian]]'' and the ''[[Book of Han]]'' describe the [[Dayuan]] as urbanized dwellers living in walled cities and having \"customs identical to those of the [[Greco-Bactrians]]\", a [[Hellenistic civilization|Hellenistic]] kingdom that was ruling [[Bactria]] at that time in today's [[Tajikistan]]. The Dayuan are also described as manufacturers and great lovers of wine.{{sfn|Watson|1993|pp=244\u201345}}\n\nDayuan was among one of the furthest western states to send envoys to the Han court. However unlike the other envoys, the ones from Dayuan did not conform to the proper Han rituals and behaved with great arrogance and self-assurance, believing they were too far away to be in any danger of invasion. Dayuan was also situated near the Xiongnu at this point, who were held in great respect for they had caused the [[Yuezhi]] much suffering. An envoy from the Xiongnu bearing the credentials of the [[Chanyu]] was provided with food and escort. In comparison, a Han envoy received no mounts he did not buy himself and no food unless he handed out silks and other goods. Han envoys also had a reputation for wealth in the west, thus they were charged exorbitant fees wherever they went, causing the Han no small amount of grief.{{sfn|Watson|1993|p=244}} However the historian [[Sima Qian]] provides a different account:\n\n{{quotation|The envoys were all sons of poor families who handled the government gifts and goods that were entrusted to them as though they were private property and looked for opportunities to buy goods at a cheap price in the foreign countries and make a profit on their return to China. The men of the foreign lands soon became disgusted when they found that each of the Han envoys told some different story and, considering that the Han armies were too far away to worry about, refused to supply the envoys with food and provisions, making things very difficult for them. The Han envoys were soon reduced to a state of destitution and distress and, their tempers mounting, fell to quarrelling and even attacking each other.{{sfn|Watson|1993|p=242}}|''[[Shiji]]''}}\n\nAmong the goods western envoys brought with them were the \"heavenly horses\", which the emperor took a liking to. He sent a trade mission with 1,000 pieces of gold and a golden horse to purchase these horses from Dayuan. Dayuan had at this point already been trading with the Han for quite some time and benefited greatly from it. Not only were they overflowing with eastern goods, they also learned from Han soldiers how to cast metal into coins and weapons. Thus they had no great reason to accept the Han trade offer, reasoning:\n\n{{quotation|The Han is far away from us and on several occasions has lost men in the salt-water wastes between our country and China. Yet if the Han parties go farther north, they will be harassed by the Xiongnu, while if they try to go south they will suffer from lack of water and fodder. Moreover, there are many places along the route where there are no cities whatsoever and they are apt to run out of provisions. The Han embassies that have come to us are made up of only a few hundred men, and yet they are always short of food and over half the men die on the journey. Under such circumstances how could the Han possibly send a large army against us? What have we to worry about? Furthermore, the horses of Ershi are one of the most valuable treasures of the state!{{sfn|Watson|1993|p=246}}|[[Dayuan]], ''[[Shiji]]''}}\n\nThe Han envoys cursed the men of Dayuan and smashed the golden horse they had brought. Enraged by this act of contempt, the nobles of Dayuan ordered Yucheng (modern [[Uzgen]]), which lay on their eastern borders, to attack and kill the envoys and seize their goods. Upon receiving word of the trade mission's demise, Emperor Wu decided to dispatch a punitive expedition against Dayuan. [[Li Guangli]], brother of Emperor Wu's favorite concubine, [[Lady Li]], was appointed Ershi General and sent against Dayuan with 6,000 cavalry and 20,000 young men drawn from the undesirables among the border kingdoms.{{sfn|Watson|1993|p=246}}\n\n==First expedition (104 BC)==\nIn the autumn of 104 BC, Li Guangli set out with an army of 6,000 cavalry and 20,000 infantry. While crossing the [[Tarim Basin]] and the [[Taklamakan Desert]] (of modern [[Xinjiang]]), Li's army was forced to attack the nearby oasis states because they refused to provide them with supplies. Sometimes they were unable to overcome the oasis states. If the siege lasted for more than a few days, the army moved on without any supplies. Due to these numerous petty conflicts, the army became exhausted and was reduced to starvation after their supplies ran out. By the time they neared Dayuan, Li had already lost too much manpower to continue the campaign. After suffering a defeat at Yucheng, Li concluded that their current strength would not be sufficient to take the Dayuan capital, Ershi ([[Khujand]]), and therefore returned to [[Dunhuang]].{{sfn|Peers|1995|p=8}}\n\n==Second expedition (102 BC)==\nThe court officials wanted to disband Li's expeditionary army and concentrate their resources toward fighting the Xiongnu. Emperor Wu refused out of fear that failure to subdue Dayuan would result in a loss of prestige with the western states. He responded by giving Li a much larger army as well as supply animals. In the autumn of 102 BC, Li set out with an army of 60,000 recruits from the prison population and 30,000 horses along with a large number of supply animals including 100,000 oxen and 20,000 donkeys and camels. This time the expedition had no problem dealing with the oasis states.{{sfn|Peers|1995|p=8}}{{sfn|Whiting|2002|p=164}}\n\nMost of them simply surrendered without a fight upon seeing the overwhelming display of power. The only state that put up any resistance was [[Luntai]], for which Li had its populace massacred. Despite meeting no major setbacks and bypassing Yucheng entirely, Li still lost half his army by the time they reached Dayuan.{{sfn|Peers|1995|p=8}} Upon arriving at Ershi, Li immediately laid siege to it. A force of [[Wusun]] cavalry 2,000 strong was also present at the request of Emperor Wu, but they refused to take part in the siege out of fear of offending either parties. Dayuan's forces sallied out in an attempt to break the siege, but they were easily defeated by Han crossbowmen. Han engineers set to work on the river passing through Ershi and diverted it, leaving the city with no source of water as they had no wells. After a 40-day siege, the Han broke through the outer wall and captured the enemy general, Jianmi. The nobles of Ershi withdrew to the inner walls and decided to offer terms of surrender. First they killed their king, Wugua, and sent his head to Li. Then they offered Li all the horses he wanted as well as supplies in return for the army's withdrawal, but if he did not accept, they would kill all their horses. Li agreed to the terms, taking some 3,000 horses as well as provisions. Before departing, Li enthroned as king one of the nobles called Meicai (\u6627\u8521), since he had previously shown kindness to the Han envoys.{{sfn|Whiting|2002|p=165}}\n\nAs Li set out for Dunhuang, he realized that the local areas along the way would not be able to adequately supply the army. The army separated into several groups, some taking the northern route while others the southern route. One of these groups, comprising only 1,000 or so men under the command of [[Wang Shensheng]] and [[Hu Chongguo]], tried to take Yucheng. After several days under siege, the inhabitants of Yucheng sallied out with 3,000 men and defeated the besieging army. A few of the Han soldiers managed to escape and alert Li of the defeat. Thereupon, Li dispatched [[Shangguan Jie]] to attack Yucheng. Seeing the great host sent against him, the king of Yucheng decided to flee to [[Kangju]], causing Yucheng to surrender shortly thereafter. When Kangju received news of Dayuan's defeat, they handed the king of Yucheng over to Shangguan, who had him executed.{{sfn|Whiting|2002|p=165}}\n\nThe army met no further opposition on the way back to [[Yumen Pass]]. Having heard of Dayuan's defeat, the rulers of the oasis states sent their kin along with the army back to the Han capital, where they presented tribute to Emperor Wu. They remained at the Han court as hostages. Despite the overall success of the second expedition, having adequate supplies and losing only a small portion of the army in battle, the entire campaign was marred by corruption and self interest. Li's soldiers, being taken from the prison population and undesirable class, were given very little care by their generals and officers, who instead abused them by withholding rations, causing desertion. As a result, Li returned with just 10,000 men and 1,000 horses fit for military service. Even so, Emperor Wu still considered these to be acceptable losses in the victory over Dayuan, and made no attempts to punish those who were responsible. Those who had survived were given handsome rewards. Li Guangli was enfeoffed as Marquis of [[Haixi Mongol and Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture|Haixi]]. [[Zhao Di]], who secured the capture of the king of Yucheng, became Marquis of [[Xinzhi]]. Shangguan Jie became privy treasurer.{{sfn|Whiting|2002|p=165}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nMore than a year later, the nobles of Dayuan banded together and killed King Meicai, who they considered responsible for the entire affair with the Han in the first place. Wugua's brother, Chanfeng, became the new king. Not wishing to upset the Han, Chanfeng sent his son as hostage to the Han court. In response, the Han dispatched envoys with gifts for the new ruler and made peace with Dayuan.{{sfn|Watson|1993|p=252}}\n\nTen years later, Li Guangli was defeated by the Xiongnu and defected to their side. He married the [[Chanyu]]'s daughter but was eventually executed over a conflict with another Han defector more favored by the Chanyu.<ref>{{cite book |author=Lin Jianming (\u6797\u5251\u9e23) |title=\u79e6\u6f22\u53f2 |trans-title=History of Qin and Han |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lqfrEY8UW1UC&pg=PA557 |year=1992 |publisher=Wunan Publishing |isbn=978-957-11-0574-1 |pages=557\u2013578}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*{{citation|last=Peers|first=C. J.|year=1995|title=Imperial Chinese Armies (1): 200 BC \u2013 AD 589|publisher=Osprey Publishing}}\n*{{citation|last=Watson|first=Burton|year=1993|title=Records of the Grand Historian by Sima Qian: Han Dynasty II (Revised Edition|publisher=Columbia University Press}} \n*{{citation|last=Whiting|first=Marvin C.|year=2002|title=Imperial Chinese Military History|publisher=Writers Club Press}}\n\n{{Han dynasty topics}}\n\n[[Category:100s BC conflicts]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Han dynasty]]\n[[Category:Wars of the Hellenistic period]]\n[[Category:Military history of Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:2nd century BC in China]]\n[[Category:Horse in Chinese mythology]]\n", "name_user": "Morrisonjohn022", "label": "safe", "comment": "phrasing and hyperlink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_of_the_Heavenly_Horses"}
{"title_page": "Yasser Seirawan", "text_new": "{{Infobox chess player\n|name = Yasser Seirawan\n|image = Seirawan0301 137.jpg\n|caption = Seirawan at the 2003 United States Chess Championship\n|birthname = \n|country = United States\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1960|3|24}}\n|birth_place = [[Damascus]], [[Syria]]\n|title = [[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]] (1980)\n|rating = \n|peakrating = 2658 (November 2011)\n|FideID = 2000032\n}}\n'''Yasser Seirawan''' ({{lang-ar|\u064a\u0627\u0633\u0631 \u0633\u064a\u0631\u0648\u0627\u0646}}; born March 24, 1960) is an American [[chess]] [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]] and four-time [[United States Chess Championship|United States champion]]. He won the [[World Junior Chess Championship]] in 1979. Seirawan is also a published chess author and commentator.\n\n==Biography and career==\nSeirawan was born in [[Damascus]], [[Syria]]. His father was Syrian and his mother an English nurse from [[Nottingham]], where he spent some time in his early childhood. When he was seven, his family immigrated to [[Seattle]] (United States), where he attended Queen Anne Elementary School, [[Edmond S. Meany Middle School|Meany Middle School]] and [[Garfield High School (Seattle, Washington)|Garfield High School]], and honed his game at a (now-defunct) coffeehouse, the [[Last Exit on Brooklyn]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Nack |first=William |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1125097/1/index.htm |title=Yasser, That's My Baby |page=3 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=December 21, 1981}}</ref> playing against the likes of [[Latvia]]n-born master [[Viktors Pupols]] and six-time [[Washington (state)|Washington]] State Champion James Harley McCormick.\n\nHe is married to [[Woman FIDE Master]] Yvette Nagel, daughter of Dutch politician [[Jan Nagel]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Anna |last=Matnadze| authorlink=Ana Matnadze|url=http://www.chessdom.com/interview-with-yasser-seirawan |title=Interview with Yasser Seirawan |website=Chessdom |date=October 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSeirawan began playing chess at 12; at 13 he became Washington junior champion. At 19 he won the [[World Junior Chess Championship]]. He also won a game against [[Viktor Korchnoi]], who had two years before narrowly lost a match for the world championship. Impressed, Viktor then invited Seirawan to Switzerland, where Korchnoi was training for his [[World Chess Championship 1981|1981 world title match]] against [[Anatoly Karpov]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=William |last=Tracy |url=http://www.saudiaramcoworld.com/issue/199002/the.right.moves.htm |work=Saudi Aramco World |volume=41 |number=2 |date=March\u2013April 1990 |title=The Right Moves}}</ref>\n\nSeirawan qualified for the 1985 and 1988-1990 [[Candidates Tournament]]s.  In the 1985 tournament in Montpellier he scored 7/15 placing joint 10th,<ref>http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chess.pl?tid=83304</ref> and in the [[World Chess Championship 1990#1988\u201390 Candidates Tournament|1988-1990 tournament in St John]], a knockout tournament, he was knocked out by [[Jon Speelman]] in the preliminary round.\n\nFor twelve years he was the chief editor of the ''Inside Chess'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldchesshof.org/exhibitions/project/lecture-series-with-yasser-seirawan/ |title=GM Yasser Seirawan Lecture Series |date=April 9, 2013 |work=World Chess Hall of Fame}}</ref> The magazine was sold to the [[ChessCafe.com]] website on which old articles were featured.\n\nIn 1999, Seirawan played a ten-game match against [[Michael Adams (chess player)|Michael Adams]] in [[Bermuda]].  The match was drawn +2\u20132=6.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Crowther |first=Mark |date=February 8, 1999 |title=TWIC 222: Adams-Seirawan in Bermuda|url=http://theweekinchess.com/html/twic222.html#6|publisher=The Week in Chess|accessdate=January 25, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref></ref>\nIn 2001, Seirawan released a plan called \"Fresh Start\" to reunite the chess world, which at that time had two [[World Chess Championship|world champions]]: [[Ruslan Ponomariov]] had gained the title under the auspices of [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale des \u00c9checs|FIDE]], while [[Vladimir Kramnik]] had beaten [[Garry Kasparov]] to take the Classical title. It called for one match between Ponomariov and Kasparov (the world number one), and another between Kramnik and the winner of the 2002 Einstein tournament in [[Dortmund]] (who turned out to be [[P\u00e9ter L\u00e9k\u00f3]]).<ref>{{cite web |first=Yasser |last=Seirawan |title=A Fresh Start for chess |url=http://en.chessbase.com/post/yaer-seirawan-proposes-i-a-fresh-start-i-for-che |website=ChessBase |date=March 2, 2002 |accessdate=January 23, 2015}}</ref> The winners of these matches would then play each other to become undisputed World Champion. This plan was signed by all parties on May 6, 2002, in the so-called \"Prague Agreement\". The Kramnik-Leko match took place (the match was drawn, with Kramnik retaining his title); the Kasparov-Ponomariov match was canceled in 2003, and this particular plan became moot when Kasparov retired in 2005. In the end the [[FIDE World Chess Championship 2006]] between Kramnik and [[Veselin Topalov]] reunited the world championship title.\n\nFollowing a series of events Seirawan participated in China during September 2003, there were reports that he would be retiring as a professional player. In the July 2007 [[FIDE]] list, Seirawan had an [[Elo rating]] of 2634, placing him in the top 100 chess players in the world, and America's number four (behind [[Hikaru Nakamura]], [[Gata Kamsky]] and [[Alexander Onischuk]]). He played six games in the July 2007 FIDE update.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIn 2007, Seirawan unveiled his [[chess variant|enhanced chess game]] called [[Seirawan chess]]. The first ever event was a 12-board simultaneous exhibition held March 31, 2007 in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia, Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chessmastery.com/seirawan-simul.html |title=GM Yasser Seirawan Gives Seirawan Chess Simultaneous |work=Chessmastery.com}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, Seirawan returned from hiatus to competitive chess, playing for the U.S. team in the world team championship in China. He had wins versus top GMs [[Judit Polgar]] and [[Shakhriyar Mamedyarov]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chess-results.com/tnr53136.aspx?art=9&lan=1&snr=38 |title=Yinzhou Cup 2011 World ChessTeam Championship \u2013 Player Info: Seirawan Yasser|website=Chess-Results.com |accessdate=July 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSeirawan won the 2011 and 2012 Dutch Open Blitz championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snelschaakmarathon.nl/SSM2011/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=151&Itemid=98 |title=Hall of fame (list of winners Dutch Open Blitzchess championship) |work=Snelschaakmarathon.nl}}</ref>\n\nSeirawan is widely known for his expert commentary in live broadcasts on the Internet during important events. He has been named by the chess historian Edward Winter as one of the top five Internet broadcasters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chesshistory.com/winter/winter127.html#9085._Live_chess_broadcasts_on |first=Edward |last=Winter |title=9085. Live chess broadcasts on the Internet |work=Chess Notes}}</ref> In 2019, he joined the Chessbrahs (headed by [[Eric Hansen (chess player)|Eric Hansen]] and [[Aman Hambleton]]), and provided coverage for the 2019 World Cup along with Hansen and Hambleton.\n\n== Books ==\nSeirawan has written several books.\n\nThe \"Winning Chess\" series (with co-author [[International Master|IM]] [[Jeremy Silman]]):\n\n*''Play Winning Chess'' - Introduction to chess and some basic strategies\n*''Winning Chess Tactics'' - Introduction to tactics with puzzles\n*''Winning Chess Strategies'' - How to use small advantages and use strategies to gain them\n*''Winning Chess Openings'' - Brief descriptions of the most popular openings, and opening strategies\n*''Winning Chess Endings'' - Introduction to the endgame\n*''Winning Chess Brilliancies'' - Notable games analyzed by the author\n*''Winning Chess Combinations'' - How to recognize the main combination patterns; somewhat of a follow up to ''Winning Chess Tactics''\n\nThe \"Winning Chess\" series was originally published by [[Microsoft Press]]; it is now published by [[Everyman Chess]].\n\n*''Five Crowns: Kasparov-Karpov World Chess Championship 1990 New York - Lyon'' (with Johathan Tisdall), International chess Enterprises, 1991. {{ISBN|978-1879479029}}\n*''Take My Rooks'' (with Nikolay Minev), International Chess Enterprises, 1991. {{ISBN|978-1879479012}}\n*''No Regrets &bull; Fischer\u2013Spassky 1992'' (with George Stefanovic), International Chess Enterprises, 1992, {{ISBN|1-879479-09-5}}\n*''Chess on the Edge'' (with Bruce Harper) - collected games of Grandmaster [[Duncan Suttles]], published by [[Chess'n Math Association]] in March 2008.\n* ''Chess Duels: My Games with the World Champions'', [[Everyman Chess]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-1857445879}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news |last=Roberts |first=Gregory |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/53957_chess10.shtml |title=Chess champ Seirawan has all the right moves |work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=January 10, 2002}}\n*{{cite news |author=Uncredited |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2ZZUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=T48DAAAAIBAJ&dq=yasser-seirawan%20last-exit&pg=6499%2C9020014 |title=Seattle chess player breathes life into musty world sport |work=[[Ellensburg Daily Record]] |date=December 31, 1982}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.365chess.com/players/Yasser_Seirawan Yasser Seirawan] chess games at 365Chess.com\n*{{Chessgames player|id=14075}}\n*[http://www.olimpbase.org/players/lzpftltg.html Yasser Seirawan] team chess record at OlimpBase.org\n*[http://www.seirawanchess.com Seirawan Chess] Enhanced Chess Devised by Yasser Seirawan in 2007\n*[http://www.gmsquare.com/interviews/seirawan2.html Interview with Yasser Seirawan] by [[Mikhail Golubev]] for GrandMaster Square\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLVWaFpMwtaGiVZ77NhhvGGGzvF7oFSWcA Lectures by GM Yasser Seirawan at the St. Louis Chess Club]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|\n  before=[[Walter Browne]], [[Larry Evans (chess grandmaster)|Larry Evans]], and [[Larry Christiansen]]|\n  title=[[United States Chess Championship|United States Chess Champion]]|\n  years=1981&ndash;1983 (with [[Walter Browne]])|\n  after=[[Walter Browne]], [[Larry Christiansen]], and [[Roman Dzindzichashvili]]\n}}\n\n{{Succession box|\n  before=[[Lev Alburt]]|\n  title=[[United States Chess Championship|United States Chess Champion]] |\n  years=1986|\n  after=[[Nick de Firmian]] and [[Joel Benjamin]]\n}}\n\n{{Succession box|\n  before=[[Michael Wilder]]|\n  title=[[United States Chess Championship|United States Chess Champion]] |\n  years=1989 (with [[Roman Dzindzichashvili]] and [[Stuart Rachels]]) |\n  after=[[Lev Alburt]]\n}}\n\n{{Succession box|\n  before=[[Boris Gulko]]|\n  title=[[United States Chess Championship|United States Chess Champion]] |\n  years=2000&ndash;2001 (with [[Joel Benjamin]] and [[Alexander Shabalov]])|\n  after=[[Larry Christiansen]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{American Chess Masters|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seirawan, Yasser}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chess grandmasters]]\n[[Category:American chess players]]\n[[Category:American chess writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:World Junior Chess Champions]]\n[[Category:Chess Olympiad competitors]]\n[[Category:Chess variant inventors]]\n[[Category:Garfield High School (Seattle) alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Damascus]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Syrian descent]]\n[[Category:Syrian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Syrian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Seattle]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox chess player\n|name = Yasser Seirawan\n|image = Seirawan0301 137.jpg\n|caption = Seirawan at the 2003 United States Chess Championship\n|birthname = \n|country = United States\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1960|3|24}}\n|birth_place = [[Damascus]], [[Syria]]\n|title = [[Grandmaster (chess)|Grandmaster]] (1980)\n|rating = \n|peakrating = 2658 (November 2011)\n|FideID = 2000032\n}}\n'''Yasser Seirawan''' ({{lang-ar|\u064a\u0627\u0633\u0631 \u0633\u064a\u0631\u0648\u0627\u0646}}; born March 24, 1960) is an American [[chess]] [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]] and four-time [[United States Chess Championship|United States champion]]. He won the [[World Junior Chess Championship]] in 1979. Seirawan is also a published chess author and commentator.\n\n==Biography and career==\nSeirawan was born in [[Damascus]], [[Syria]]. His father was Syrian and his mother an English nurse from [[Nottingham]], where he spent some time in his early childhood. When he was seven, his family immigrated to [[Seattle]] (United States), where he attended Queen Anne Elementary School, [[Edmond S. Meany Middle School|Meany Middle School]] and [[Garfield High School (Seattle, Washington)|Garfield High School]], and honed his game at a (now-defunct) coffeehouse, the [[Last Exit on Brooklyn]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Nack |first=William |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1125097/1/index.htm |title=Yasser, That's My Baby |page=3 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=December 21, 1981}}</ref> playing against the likes of [[Latvia]]n-born master [[Viktors Pupols]] and six-time [[Washington (state)|Washington]] State Champion James Harley McCormick.\n\nHe is married to [[Woman FIDE Master]] Yvette Nagel, daughter of Dutch politician [[Jan Nagel]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Anna |last=Matnadze| authorlink=Ana Matnadze|url=http://www.chessdom.com/interview-with-yasser-seirawan |title=Interview with Yasser Seirawan |website=Chessdom |date=October 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSeirawan began playing chess at 12; at 13 he became Washington junior champion. At 19 he won the [[World Junior Chess Championship]]. He also won a game against [[Viktor Korchnoi]], who had two years before narrowly lost a match for the world championship. Impressed, Viktor </ref><ref></ref></ref>then invited Seirawan to Switzerland, where Korchnoi was training for his [[World Chess Championship 1981|1981 world title match]] against [[Anatoly Karpov]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=William |last=Tracy |url=http://www.saudiaramcoworld.com/issue/199002/the.right.moves.htm |work=Saudi Aramco World |volume=41 |number=2 |date=March\u2013April 1990 |title=The Right Moves}}</ref>\n\nSeirawan qualified for the 1985 and 1988-1990 [[Candidates Tournament]]s.  In the 1985 tournament in Montpellier he scored 7/15 placing joint 10th,<ref>http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chess.pl?tid=83304</ref> and in the [[World Chess Championship 1990#1988\u201390 Candidates Tournament|1988-1990 tournament in St John]], a knockout tournament, he was knocked out by [[Jon Speelman]] in the preliminary round.\n\nFor twelve years he was the chief editor of the ''Inside Chess'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldchesshof.org/exhibitions/project/lecture-series-with-yasser-seirawan/ |title=GM Yasser Seirawan Lecture Series |date=April 9, 2013 |work=World Chess Hall of Fame}}</ref> The magazine was sold to the [[ChessCafe.com]] website on which old articles were featured.\n\nIn 1999, Seirawan played a ten-game match against [[Michael Adams (chess player)|Michael Adams]] in [[Bermuda]].  The match was drawn +2\u20132=6.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Crowther |first=Mark |date=February 8, 1999 |title=TWIC 222: Adams-Seirawan in Bermuda|url=http://theweekinchess.com/html/twic222.html#6|publisher=The Week in Chess|accessdate=January 25, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref></ref>\nIn 2001, Seirawan released a plan called \"Fresh Start\" to reunite the chess world, which at that time had two [[World Chess Championship|world champions]]: [[Ruslan Ponomariov]] had gained the title under the auspices of [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale des \u00c9checs|FIDE]], while [[Vladimir Kramnik]] had beaten [[Garry Kasparov]] to take the Classical title. It called for one match between Ponomariov and Kasparov (the world number one), and another between Kramnik and the winner of the 2002 Einstein tournament in [[Dortmund]] (who turned out to be [[P\u00e9ter L\u00e9k\u00f3]]).<ref>{{cite web |first=Yasser |last=Seirawan |title=A Fresh Start for chess |url=http://en.chessbase.com/post/yaer-seirawan-proposes-i-a-fresh-start-i-for-che |website=ChessBase |date=March 2, 2002 |accessdate=January 23, 2015}}</ref> The winners of these matches would then play each other to become undisputed World Champion. This plan was signed by all parties on May 6, 2002, in the so-called \"Prague Agreement\". The Kramnik-Leko match took place (the match was drawn, with Kramnik retaining his title); the Kasparov-Ponomariov match was canceled in 2003, and this particular plan became moot when Kasparov retired in 2005. In the end the [[FIDE World Chess Championship 2006]] between Kramnik and [[Veselin Topalov]] reunited the world championship title.\n\nFollowing a series of events Seirawan participated in China during September 2003, there were reports that he would be retiring as a professional player. In the July 2007 [[FIDE]] list, Seirawan had an [[Elo rating]] of 2634, placing him in the top 100 chess players in the world, and America's number four (behind [[Hikaru Nakamura]], [[Gata Kamsky]] and [[Alexander Onischuk]]). He played six games in the July 2007 FIDE update.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIn 2007, Seirawan unveiled his [[chess variant|enhanced chess game]] called [[Seirawan chess]]. The first ever event was a 12-board simultaneous exhibition held March 31, 2007 in [[Vancouver]], British Columbia, Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chessmastery.com/seirawan-simul.html |title=GM Yasser Seirawan Gives Seirawan Chess Simultaneous |work=Chessmastery.com}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, Seirawan returned from hiatus to competitive chess, playing for the U.S. team in the world team championship in China. He had wins versus top GMs [[Judit Polgar]] and [[Shakhriyar Mamedyarov]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chess-results.com/tnr53136.aspx?art=9&lan=1&snr=38 |title=Yinzhou Cup 2011 World ChessTeam Championship \u2013 Player Info: Seirawan Yasser|website=Chess-Results.com |accessdate=July 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSeirawan won the 2011 and 2012 Dutch Open Blitz championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snelschaakmarathon.nl/SSM2011/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=151&Itemid=98 |title=Hall of fame (list of winners Dutch Open Blitzchess championship) |work=Snelschaakmarathon.nl}}</ref>\n\nSeirawan is widely known for his expert commentary in live broadcasts on the Internet during important events. He has been named by the chess historian Edward Winter as one of the top five Internet broadcasters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chesshistory.com/winter/winter127.html#9085._Live_chess_broadcasts_on |first=Edward |last=Winter |title=9085. Live chess broadcasts on the Internet |work=Chess Notes}}</ref> In 2019, he joined the Chessbrahs (headed by [[Eric Hansen (chess player)|Eric Hansen]] and [[Aman Hambleton]]), and provided coverage for the 2019 World Cup along with Hansen and Hambleton.\n\n== Books ==\nSeirawan has written several books.\n\nThe \"Winning Chess\" series (with co-author [[International Master|IM]] [[Jeremy Silman]]):\n\n*''Play Winning Chess'' - Introduction to chess and some basic strategies\n*''Winning Chess Tactics'' - Introduction to tactics with puzzles\n*''Winning Chess Strategies'' - How to use small advantages and use strategies to gain them\n*''Winning Chess Openings'' - Brief descriptions of the most popular openings, and opening strategies\n*''Winning Chess Endings'' - Introduction to the endgame\n*''Winning Chess Brilliancies'' - Notable games analyzed by the author\n*''Winning Chess Combinations'' - How to recognize the main combination patterns; somewhat of a follow up to ''Winning Chess Tactics''\n\nThe \"Winning Chess\" series was originally published by [[Microsoft Press]]; it is now published by [[Everyman Chess]].\n\n*''Five Crowns: Kasparov-Karpov World Chess Championship 1990 New York - Lyon'' (with Johathan Tisdall), International chess Enterprises, 1991. {{ISBN|978-1879479029}}\n*''Take My Rooks'' (with Nikolay Minev), International Chess Enterprises, 1991. {{ISBN|978-1879479012}}\n*''No Regrets &bull; Fischer\u2013Spassky 1992'' (with George Stefanovic), International Chess Enterprises, 1992, {{ISBN|1-879479-09-5}}\n*''Chess on the Edge'' (with Bruce Harper) - collected games of Grandmaster [[Duncan Suttles]], published by [[Chess'n Math Association]] in March 2008.\n* ''Chess Duels: My Games with the World Champions'', [[Everyman Chess]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-1857445879}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news |last=Roberts |first=Gregory |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/53957_chess10.shtml |title=Chess champ Seirawan has all the right moves |work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=January 10, 2002}}\n*{{cite news |author=Uncredited |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2ZZUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=T48DAAAAIBAJ&dq=yasser-seirawan%20last-exit&pg=6499%2C9020014 |title=Seattle chess player breathes life into musty world sport |work=[[Ellensburg Daily Record]] |date=December 31, 1982}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.365chess.com/players/Yasser_Seirawan Yasser Seirawan] chess games at 365Chess.com\n*{{Chessgames player|id=14075}}\n*[http://www.olimpbase.org/players/lzpftltg.html Yasser Seirawan] team chess record at OlimpBase.org\n*[http://www.seirawanchess.com Seirawan Chess] Enhanced Chess Devised by Yasser Seirawan in 2007\n*[http://www.gmsquare.com/interviews/seirawan2.html Interview with Yasser Seirawan] by [[Mikhail Golubev]] for GrandMaster Square\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLVWaFpMwtaGiVZ77NhhvGGGzvF7oFSWcA Lectures by GM Yasser Seirawan at the St. Louis Chess Club]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|\n  before=[[Walter Browne]], [[Larry Evans (chess grandmaster)|Larry Evans]], and [[Larry Christiansen]]|\n  title=[[United States Chess Championship|United States Chess Champion]]|\n  years=1981&ndash;1983 (with [[Walter Browne]])|\n  after=[[Walter Browne]], [[Larry Christiansen]], and [[Roman Dzindzichashvili]]\n}}\n\n{{Succession box|\n  before=[[Lev Alburt]]|\n  title=[[United States Chess Championship|United States Chess Champion]] |\n  years=1986|\n  after=[[Nick de Firmian]] and [[Joel Benjamin]]\n}}\n\n{{Succession box|\n  before=[[Michael Wilder]]|\n  title=[[United States Chess Championship|United States Chess Champion]] |\n  years=1989 (with [[Roman Dzindzichashvili]] and [[Stuart Rachels]]) |\n  after=[[Lev Alburt]]\n}}\n\n{{Succession box|\n  before=[[Boris Gulko]]|\n  title=[[United States Chess Championship|United States Chess Champion]] |\n  years=2000&ndash;2001 (with [[Joel Benjamin]] and [[Alexander Shabalov]])|\n  after=[[Larry Christiansen]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{American Chess Masters|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seirawan, Yasser}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chess grandmasters]]\n[[Category:American chess players]]\n[[Category:American chess writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:World Junior Chess Champions]]\n[[Category:Chess Olympiad competitors]]\n[[Category:Chess variant inventors]]\n[[Category:Garfield High School (Seattle) alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Damascus]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Syrian descent]]\n[[Category:Syrian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Syrian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Seattle]]\n", "name_user": "William in Seattle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography and career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yasser_Seirawan"}
{"title_page": "Sarath Fonseka", "text_new": "{{For|disambiguation|Sarath (disambiguation){{!}}Sarath}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{EngvarB |date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix  = [[The Honourable|Hon.]] [[Field Marshal (Sri Lanka)|Field Marshal]] \n| birth_name        = Gardihewa Sarath Chandralal Fonseka\n| honorific-suffix  = [[Rana Wickrama Padakkama|RWP]], [[Rana Sura Padakkama|RSP]], [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya|VSV]], [[Uttama Seva Padakkama|USP]], [[Member of Parliament|MP]], [[Royal College of Defence Studies|rcds]], [[Psc (British Army)|psc]]\n| native_name = {{lang|si|\u0dc3\u0dbb\u0dad\u0dca \u0dc6\u0ddc\u0db1\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dda\u0d9a\u0dcf}}\n| image             = Fonseka Press Conference.jpg\n| alt               =\n| caption           = <span style=\"font-size:88%\">Fonseka at a press conference</span>\n| office10          =  Leader of the [[Democratic Party (Sri Lanka)|Democratic Party]]\n| predecessor10     = '''Office Created'''\n| successor10       = '''Office Dissolved'''\n| term_start10      = 1 April 2013\n| term_end10        = 30 April 2016\n| office1           = Minister of Wildlife and Sustainable Development\n| president1        = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister1    = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start1       = 1 May 2018\n| term_end1         = 26 October 2018\n| predecessor1      = [[Ravindra Samaraweera]]\n| successor1        = \n| office2           = [[Ministry of Urban Development (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Regional Development]]\n| president2        = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister2    = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start2       = 25 February 2016\n| term_end2         = 26 October 2018\n| predecessor2      = '''Office Established'''\n| successor2        = \n| constituency_MP  = [[National List Member of Parliament|National List]]\n| parliament       = Sri Lanka\n| majority         = \n| predecessor      = M.K.A.D.S. Gunawardana\n| successor        = \n| term_start       = 9 February 2016\n| term_end         =\n| constituency_MP3  = [[Colombo Electoral District|Colombo District]]\n| parliament3       = Sri Lanka\n| majority3         = 98,456 Preferential Votes\n| predecessor3      = \n| successor3        = Jayantha Katagoda\n| term_start3       = 22 April 2010\n| term_end3         = 7 October 2010\n| office4           = [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of the Defence Staff]]\n| term_start4       = 15 July 2009\n| term_end4         = 30 November 2009\n| predecessor4      = [[Donald Perera]]\n| successor4        = [[Roshan Goonetileke]]\n| office5           = [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lanka Army]]\n| term_start5       = 6 December 2005\n| term_end5         = 15 July 2009\n| predecessor5      = [[Shantha Kottegoda]]\n| successor5        = [[Jagath Jayasuriya]]\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1950|12|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place       = [[Ambalangoda]], [[Southern Province, Sri Lanka|Southern Province]], [[Dominion of Ceylon]]<br/>(now [[Sri Lanka]])\n| nationality       = Sri Lankan\n| death_date        =\n| death_place       = \n| alma_mater        = Madawalalanda Maha Vidyalaya, Ampara <!-- Ref: http://www.lankatruth.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4235:general-fonseka-visits-his-first-school-in-ampara-meets-classmate&catid=35:local&Itemid=50 --> [[Dharmasoka College|Dharmasoka College, Ambalangoda]]<br />[[Ananda College|Ananda College, Colombo]]\n| party            = [[United National Party]] <br /> <small>(2016 - Present )</small> <br />[[Democratic Party (Sri Lanka)|Democratic Party]] <br /> <small>(2013 - 2016)</small> <br /> [[Democratic National Alliance (Sri Lanka)|Democratic National Alliance]] <br /> <small>(2010 - 2013)</small> <br /> [[New Democratic Front (Sri Lanka)|New Democratic Front]] <br /> <small> (2009\u20132010) </small><ref group=\"N\">Only for the 2010 Presidential Election</ref>\n| otherparty       = [[United National Front (Sri Lanka)|United National Front]] <br /> <small>(2016 - Present)</small>\n| relations        =\n| spouse           = [[Anoma Fonseka]]\n| children         = Aparna Fonseka<br />Apsara Fonseka\n| residence        =\n| occupation       = [[Politician]]<br/> [[Military Officer]]\n| signature        =\n| signature_alt    =\n| website          =\n| footnotes        =\n| allegiance       = Sri Lanka\n| branch           = {{army|Sri Lanka}}\n| unit             = [[Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment]]\n| serviceyears     = 1970\u20132009,<br />2015\u2013Present{{efn|Sri Lankan military officers of [[five-star rank]] hold their rank for life, and are considered to be serving officers until their deaths.}}\n| rank             = [[File:Sri_Lanka-army-OF-10.svg|10px]] [[Field Marshal (Sri Lanka)|Field Marshal]] \n| battles          = [[Sri Lankan Civil War]],<br />[[1987\u201389 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|Insurrection 1987\u201389]]\n| commands         = [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Army]]<br />[[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of the Defence Staff]]\n| mawards          =\n {{plainlist |\n* [[File:Rana wickrama medal.svg|25px]] [[Rana Wickrama Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Rana sura medal.svg|25px]] [[Rana Sura Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya medal bar.svg|25px]] [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya]]\n* [[File:Uttama Seva ribbon bar.svg|25px]] [[Uttama Seva Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Desha Putra Sammanaya ribbon bar.svg|25px]] [[Desha Putra Sammanaya]]\n }}\n}}\n[[Field marshal (Sri Lanka)|Field Marshal]]  '''Gardihewa Sarath Chandralal Fonseka''', [[Rana Wickrama Padakkama|RWP]], [[Rana Sura Padakkama|RSP]], [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya|VSV]], [[Uttama Seva Padakkama|USP]], [[Member of Parliament|MP]], [[Royal College of Defence Studies|rcds]], [[Psc (British Army)|psc]] ({{lang-si|\u0d9c\u0dbb\u0dca\u0daf\u0dd2\u0dc4\u0dda\u0dc0\u0dcf \u0dc3\u0dbb\u0dad\u0dca \u0da0\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb\u0dbd\u0dcf\u0dbd\u0dca \u0dc6\u0ddc\u0db1\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dda\u0d9a\u0dcf}}, {{lang-ta|\u0b9a\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bca\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bc7\u0b95\u0bbe}}; born 18 December 1950), commonly known as '''Sarath Fonseka''', is a [[Sri Lanka]]n politician and a military leader. He was the eighteenth [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of Sri Lankan Army]], and under his command the Sri Lankan Army ended the 26-year [[Sri Lankan Civil War]] in 2009, defeating the rebel [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]]; he thereafter briefly served as the [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of Defence Staff]].<ref name=Defence>[http://www.defence.lk/main_abt.asp?fname=CDS_General General G. S. C. Fonseka RWP RSP VSV USP rcds psc], Ministry of Defence, Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref> After retiring from the Army with the rank of General, he entered politics as the common opposition candidate in the [[2010 Sri Lankan presidential election|2010 presidential election]] contesting against President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]. Following his controversial defeat in the presidential election he was elected to Parliament in the general election that followed. Soon after he was made a political prisoner and lost his parliamentary seat.<ref name=hero>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/100919/News/nws_16.html Prosecuting and persecuting the war hero \u2013 General Fonseka], By Somar Wijayadasa, [[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/south-asia/Sarath-Fonseka-becomes-Lankas-first-field-marshal/articleshow/46656265.cms Sarath Fonseka becomes Lanka\u2019s first field marshal] - [[The Times of India]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=Khaleej>[http://www.khaleejtimes.com/mobile/inside.asp?xfile=/data/international/2015/March/international_March538.xml&section=international& Fonseka to become first Sri Lankan Field Marshal], [[Khaleej Times]] (UAE), Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref> Fonseka supported [[Maithripala Sirisena]] in the [[2015 Sri Lankan presidential election|2015 presidential election]] and following his victory, the newly appointed President Sirisena gave Fonseka a full pardon reinstating his civic rights, military rank and decorations. Later he was promoted to the newly created rank of [[Field Marshal (Sri Lanka)|Field Marshal]] on 22 March 2015 becoming the first [[Sri Lankan Army]] officer to be promoted to the rank.<ref name=elevated>[http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=Gen_GSC_Fonseka_elevated_to_the_rank_of_Field_Marshal_20150322_01 Gen. GSC Fonseka elevated to the rank of 'Field Marshal'], Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka), Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=Portal>[http://www.news.lk/news/sri-lanka/item/6710-sarath-fonseka-to-be-bestowed-with-field-marshal-title Sarath Fonseka to be bestowed with Field Marshal Title] NEWS.LK (The Official Government News Portal of Sri Lanka), Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=Express>[http://www.newindianexpress.com/world/General-Fonseka-Made-Field-Marshal/2015/03/22/article2725227.ece General Fonseka Made Field Marshal] - P.K.Balachandran, [[The Indian Express]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref>\n\nOn 9 February 2016 he was appointed to Parliament as a [[National List Member of Parliament|national list candidate]] and served in the [[Cabinet of Sri Lanka|Cabinet of Ministers]] from 2016 to 2018 as Minister of Regional Development and thereafter as Minister of Wildlife and Sustainable Development until the [[2018 Sri Lankan constitutional crisis]].\n\nFonseka had joined the Sri Lanka Army in 1970 and was commissioned as a [[second lieutenant]] in June 1971 and rose through the ranks while completing training stints across [[South Asia]] and in the [[United States]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. He saw extensive action throughout the 26-year civil war and over the years acquired a reputation as a tough battlefield commander and was often in the thick of the action in fighting against the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam|Tamil Tigers]], culminating in a term as Commander of the Army from 6 December 2005 \u2013 15 July 2009.<ref name=Frontline>[http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl1710/17100100.htm The taking of Elephant Pass], D.B.S. JEYARAJ [[Frontline (magazine)]], Volume 17 - Issue 10, May. 13 - 26, 2000, Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=early>[http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2009/06/21/sec20.asp Army Commander revisits early beginnings], Shanika SRIYANANDA, [[Sunday Observer (Sri Lanka)|Sunday Observer]], Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref name=\"FM1\">[http://www.army.lk/detailed.php?NewsId=9469 Nation Salutes War Veteran, General Sarath Fonseka (Retd) Conferring Field Marshal Rank], army.lk, Retrieved 25 March 2015</ref> As commander, he oversaw the [[Eelam War IV|final phase]] of the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]], which resulted in the total defeat of the militant [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]]. He also survived an assassination attempt when an LTTE suicide bomber attacked his motorcade in April 2006.<ref name=Sydney>[https://www.smh.com.au/news/world/sri-lankas-top-general-wounded-in-suicide-attack/2006/04/25/1145861341920.html Sri Lanka's top general wounded in suicide attack], [[The Sydney Morning Herald]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=Medical>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/archive/20060507/politics.htm Medical battle that saved the Army Commander] By Chinthaka Fernando, [[The Sunday Leader]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=Taught>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/05/22/AR2009052202033.html|title=Mia Bloom \u2013 What the Tigers Taught Al-Qaeda|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=24 May 2009 }}</ref> Following the end of the war Fonseka was promoted to a four star rank in the Sri Lanka Army, becoming the first serving officer to hold a four star rank.<ref name=ever>[http://news.lk/news/sri-lanka/item/6744-sarath-fonseka-promoted-sri-lanka-s-first-ever-field-marshal Sarath Fonseka promoted Sri Lanka's first ever Field Marshal], NEWS.LK (The Official Government News Portal of Sri Lanka), Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090518_16 Armed Force Commanders promoted to next higher ranks]. Ministry of Defence, Public Security, Law & Order, Retrieved on 18 May 2009</ref> He has been described as Sri Lanka's most successful army commander.<ref name=Khaleej/><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-30912331 Sri Lanka rehabilitates ex-army chief Sarath Fonseka], Charles Haviland, [[BBC News]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=\"Victory\">{{cite book|title=Lost Victory: The Rise & Fall of LTTE Supremo, V. Prabhakaran|author=Mehta, Maj. Gen. (Retd) Raj K.|pages=13, 118, 330\u2013338, 360\u20138, 377, 380, 401\u201311|publisher=Pentagon Press|isbn=978-8182744431}}</ref><ref name=Review>[http://asiantribune.com/news/2012/06/02/lalins-column-review-gota%E2%80%99s-war-final-revised Review - Gota\u2019s War -Final- revised] By Major General (Retired) Lalin Fernando, Asian Tribune, Retrieved 18 May 2015</ref>\n\nA few months after the defeat of the Tamil Tigers, Fonseka was appointed [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|\nChief of Defence Staff]] by President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]. While his new post was of a higher rank, Fonseka saw the move as an attempt to sideline him. Amid rumours of his desire to enter politics, he subsequently retired from the post on 16 November 2009.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8361862.stm|title=S Lanka army head leaves abruptly|last=Haviland|first=Charles|date=16 November 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC News November\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8356570.stm|title=Sri Lanka military chief resigns|date=12 November 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref> On 29 November 2009, Fonseka formally announced his candidature in the [[2010 Sri Lankan presidential election|2010 Sri Lankan Presidential Election]]. His candidacy was endorsed by the main opposition parties, and Fonseka became the main opposition candidate challenging President Rajapaksa. He campaigned under the sign of a swan, and the slogan ''Vishvasaniya Venasak'' (A Credible Change).\n\nFollowing his election defeat, Fonseka was arrested on 8 February 2010, and the government announced he would be [[court-martial]]ed for committing \"military offences\".<ref>[http://www.nationalsecurity.lk/fullnews.php?id=23456 Former Army Commander General Sarath Fonseka in military custody], Media Center for National Security</ref><ref name=Lion>[http://www.dailymirror.lk/105390/The-night-the-Ambalangoda-Lion-roared-defiance THE NIGHT THE AMBALANGODA LION ROARED DEFIANCE] - D.B.S. Jeyaraj (Daily Mirror) Retrieved 14 February 2016</ref> He was convicted for corrupt military supply deals and sentenced to three years in prison.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iNE2z6YPPccyYObraBkLB7jEVadg Sri Lanka jails ex-army chief Fonseka] AFP \u2013 17 September 2010</ref>\nAfter serving more than 2 years in prison, Fonseka was released amidst local and international pressure on 21 May 2012.<ref name=Express/><ref name=chief>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/mar/23/ex-army-chief-sarath-fonseka-jailed-for-treason-made-field-marshal-in-sri-lanka#img-1 Ex-army chief Sarath Fonseka, jailed for treason, made field marshal in Sri Lanka], [[The Guardian]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref> As per the pre-election statement, President [[Maithripala Sirisena]], gave him the Complete Presidential Pardon and acquitted him of all the charges against him on 22 January 2015, restoring his Civic Rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news.lk/news/business/item/5835-sarath-fonseka-acquitted-of-all-charges|title=Sarath Fonseka acquitted of all charges|website=www.news.lk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-30912331|title=Sri Lanka rehabilitates top general|date=21 January 2015|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nFonseka was born on 18 December 1950 in the coastal town of [[Ambalangoda]] in the south of Sri Lanka. His father was Peter Fonseka, a school principal and his mother Piyawathie Fonseka was a teacher. He initially attended Madawalalanda Maha Vidyalaya (1955\u20131957) in [[Ampara]],<ref>[http://www.lankatruth.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4235:general-fonseka-visits-his-first-school-in-ampara-meets-classmate&catid=35:local&Itemid=50 General Fonseka visits his first school in Ampara]. Lanka Truth, Retrieved on 7 January 2010.</ref> later receiving his secondary education from [[Dharmasoka College|Dharmasoka College, Ambalangoda]] (1958\u20131965) and [[Ananda College|Ananda College, Colombo]] (1966\u20131969). Fonseka represented his alma mater in [[National Cadet Corps (Sri Lanka)|cadeting]], swimming and [[water polo]] events. He was the college swimming and water polo captain in 1969 and later represented the [[Military of Sri Lanka|defence services]] and the country in these sports.<ref name=Defence/> He was a [[Sergeant]] of the [[National Cadet Corps (Sri Lanka)|College Cadet Platoon]].<ref>[http://archives.dailynews.lk/2009/07/03/Sup.asp?id=s13 Meteoric rise of Ananda's patriotic sons], Rasika SOMARATNA, [[Daily News (Sri Lanka)|Daily News]], Retrieved 4 May 2015</ref><ref name=inspires>[http://archives.dailynews.lk/2009/07/03/Sup.asp?id=s17 Ananda inspires students to serve the Nation], [[Daily News (Sri Lanka)|Daily News]], Retrieved 4 May 2015</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n===Early years===\nFonseka joined a [[Ceylon Army]] on 5 February 1970 as a [[cadet officer]] and after completing his basic officer training at the [[Sri Lanka Military Academy|Army Training Centre]] in [[Diyatalawa]], he was commissioned as a [[Second Lieutenant]] in the 1st Battalion, [[Ceylon Sinha Regiment]] on 1 June 1971 during the [[1971 Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna Insurrection|1971 Insurrection]].<ref name=\"FM1\"/>\n\nServing with as [[platoon commander]] in the Sinha Regiment, he was promoted to [[Lieutenant]] in 1973 and was promoted to the rank of [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]] in 1976. During this time he underwent the [[Commando]] Officers Course (1973), Battalion Support Weapons Course (1976) and Counter Insurgency Jungle Warfare Course (1978) in India. In 1980 he was promoted to the rank of [[Major]] and in 1981 he attend the Company Commanders Course in Pakistan. In the next few years he served as an [[Drill instructor|instructor]] at the [[Sri Lanka Military Academy]], Ampara Combat Training School and [[Infantry Training Centre (Sri Lanka Army)|Infantry Training Centre]], and later as the Chief Instructor and Deputy Commandant in the same training institutes.<ref name=\"FM1\"/>\n\n===Eelam War I===\nIn 1987, he graduated from [[Defence Services Command and Staff College (Bangladesh)|Defence Services Command and Staff College]], [[Mirpur Model Thana|Mirpur]] in Bangladesh. On his return was appointed [[Commanding Officer]], [[Sri Lanka Light Infantry|4th Sri Lanka Light Infantry]] and participated in the [[Vadamarachchi Operation]].[http://www.elakiri.com/forum/picture.php?albumid=1886&pictureid=7812]<ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/090628/Plus/sundaytimesplus_08.html Operation Liberation One], [[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)|The Sunday Times]], Retrieved 6 April 2015</ref><ref>[http://oaaj.org/speech.html Full text of H.E\u0081fs speech at the War Heroes commemoration event at the Ananda College], Old Anandians Web Japan, Retrieved 6 April 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090703_07 Sri Lanka taught world the art of humane ops-President], Ministry of Defence, Retrieved 6 April 2015</ref> The following year he was promoted to [[Lieutenant Colonel]] and appointed Commanding Officer, 1st Battalion, Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment in 1989.\n\nWith the on set of the [[1987\u201389 JVP Insurrection]], he was appointed as military coordinating officer for [[Gampaha District]].<ref name=\"FM1\"/> Fonseka reputedly devised the plan which led to the capture of [[Premakumar Gunaratnam]] and gained a reputation for his [[humane]] treatment of detainees.<ref>[http://www.dailymirror.lk/62597/fsp-leader-kumar-gunaratnam-fought-a-guerilla-war-against-the-indian-army FSP leader Kumar Gunaratnam fought a Guerilla war against the Indian army: Security Forces], By D.B.S.Jeyaraj, [[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref>\n\n===Eelam War II===\nIn 1991, he was promoted to [[Colonel]] and served as a [[brigade commander]], 3rd Brigade during [[Operation Balavegaya]] and distinguished himself as a Brigade Commander. In the [[First Battle of Elephant Pass]], the Sri Lankan armed forces were able to beat back the LTTE owing to the tenacity of the besieged troops led by Fonseka and the grit with which they held on despite the overwhelming odds.<ref name=Frontline/> Thereafter he was appointed as Center Commandant, Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment at [[Ambepussa]] and next served as Staff Officer I at the Directorate of Operations at the [[Army Headquarters, Colombo|Army Headquarters]].\n\nIn 1993, the [[Jaffna Fort]] was under siege by Tamil Tiger rebels. Then [[Colonel]] Fonseka led troops in the daring [[Midnight Express (military operation)|Midnight Express]] operation to relieve besieged troops. Several hundred soldiers were saved due to the operation. Colonel Fonseka was wounded that year in the Yaldevi operation, having been shot through the lung. At the time Fonseka was commanding the [[23 Division (Sri Lanka)|23 Division]]. After recovering, he was promoted to [[Brigadier]] in December 1993 and was appointed to the Operational Headquarters in Colombo.<ref name=\"FM1\"/>\n\n===Eelam War III===\n[[Brigadier]] Fonseka was soon deployed to operational areas serving as Commander - Area Headquarters, [[Mannar, Sri Lanka|Mannar]]; [[General Officer Commanding]], 5 Division in Mannar; General Officer Commanding, [[21 Division (Sri Lanka)|21 Division]]; Deputy Commander, Task Force I; General Officer Commanding, 3 Division in [[Batticaloa]]; General Officer Commanding, 27 Division in [[Kilinochchi]]; Coordinating Officer for [[Kayts]] and [[Mandattivu]], Deputy General Officer Commanding, [[51 Division (Sri Lanka)|51 Division]] in [[Jaffna]], General Officer Commanding, [[23 Division (Sri Lanka)|23 Division]] in [[Polonnaruwa]]; Overlooking General Officer Commanding [[Vavuniya]] Task Force - 2; General Officer Commanding, [[55 Division (Sri Lanka)|55 Division]] at [[Mirusuvil]].\n\nIn 1995 Brigadier Fonseka won widespread plaudits for his role in [[Operation Riviresa]] - the army's operation to capture Jaffna town from the Tamil Tigers.<ref name=inspires/> He played a major role in [[Operation Jayasikurui]].<ref name=\"FM1\"/> In 1998, he was promoted to the rank of [[Major General]]. He was appointed [[Colonel of the Regiment]] of the Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment. Serving as General Officer Commanding, [[22 Division (Sri Lanka)|22 Division]] and [[Director General]], [[General Staff]] at the Army Headquarters.\n\nIn 2000, with the imminent fall of [[Elephant Pass]], Major General Fonseka was rushed in as Commander, [[Security Forces Headquarters - Jaffna ]] and successfully defended the [[Jaffna peninsula]] from the massive offensive [[Operation Unceasing Waves III]] launched by the LTTE.<ref name=Frontline/><ref name=early/><ref name=Guardian>[http://www.slguardian.org/?p=15274 We built too many walls and not enough bridges], By Keerthi Ratnayaka, [[Sri Lanka Guardian]], Retrieved 31 March 2015</ref> Thereafter he served as Commander, [[Security Forces Headquarters - Wanni]]. From May 2002 to November 2003 after he was again appointed the Commander, Security Forces Headquarters  - Jaffna, Fonseka strengthened the defences of Jaffna<ref name=early/><ref name=inspires/><ref name=Guardian/><ref name=HSZ>[http://slwaronterror.blogspot.co.uk/2015/03/jaffna-hsz-reduced-further.html 2002-2003 controversy over Jaffna HSZ] by Shamindra Ferdinando, [[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]], Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.lankaweb.com/news/items03/160203-2.html LTTE DEMONSTRATIONS IN JAFFNA AND VAVUNIYA BURN EFFIGIES OF JAFFNA COMMANDER SARATH FONSEKA AND DEMAND ARMY TO QUIT], By Walter Jayawardhana, (LankaWeb), Retrieved 31 March 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/021229/columns/sitrep.html HSZ row: Story behind the story] The Sunday Times, Retrieved 24 February 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/countries/shrilanka/document/papers/MG_sarath.htm De-escalation Plan proposed by Security Forces Commander, Jaffna Peninsula, Maj. Gen. Sarath Fonseka, to Enable Re-settlement of Civilians in High Security Zones, December 20, 2002] South Asia Terrorism Portal, Retrieved 24 February 2016</ref> and launched a new training programme for the [[infantry]].<ref name=\"The Man of the Moment\">[http://businesstoday.lk/cover_page.php?issue=202#sthash.cqHoVGsC.dpuf The Man of the Moment : Lieutenant General Sarath Fonseka], Business Today, Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref name=Innovations>[http://www.benning.army.mil/infantry/magazine/issues/2013/May-June/Welch.html Infantry Innovations: Sri Lanka\u2019s Experience] by LTC (Retired) Ivan Welch, U.S. Army Infantry Magazine, Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref name=Analysis>[http://www.futuredirections.org.au/files/1266992558-FDIStrategicAnalysisPaper-12February2010.pdf Strategic Analysis of Sri Lankan Military\u2019s Counter-Insurgency Operations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328123409/http://futuredirections.org.au/files/1266992558-FDIStrategicAnalysisPaper-12February2010.pdf |date=28 March 2015 }}, Sergei DeSilva-Ranasinghe, Future Directions International, Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref>\n\nThereafter he attended the [[Royal College of Defence Studies]] in London and on his return he was appointed Commandant, [[Defence Services Command and Staff College]].<ref name=\"FM1\"/> In 2003, he was appointed Commandant, [[Sri Lanka Army Volunteer Force]] and in 2004 he was appointed Director Infantry, Deputy Chief of Staff and then [[Chief of Staff]] of the Sri Lanka Army. In December 2005 he was appointed Commander of the Army by president Mahinda  Rajapaksa and was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant General]]<ref name=\"The Man of the Moment\"/>\n\n;Suicide bomb attack\n{{See also|Chaminda Ruwan Yakandawala}}\n\nOn 25 April 2006, Lt. General Fonseka survived an LTTE suicide bomb attack on his unarmored [[staff car]] by a pregnant LTTE operative named Anoja Kugenthirarasah who infiltrated Army Headquarters by attending the regular maternity clinic provided for civilians at the military hospital.<ref name=Taught/><ref>[http://www.tamilguardian.com/article.asp?articleid=632 Fonseka still critical after suicide bomb attack], [[Tamil Guardian]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,501060508-1189385,00.html If This is Called Peace], [[Time Magazine]], Retrieved on 30 April 2006.</ref> Fonseka was gravely wounded in the attack along with his [[Aide-de-camp|ADC]]; while nine others, including members of his security detail were killed.<ref name=Sydney/> The General was rushed to the [[Colombo General Hospital]] within minutes. This had been possible because the attack took place next to the Army Hospital and therefore an ambulance was at hand. Fonseka was conscious upon admittance and had communicated with his officers and the doctors. The general, who was unconscious following emergency surgery, was put on a ventilator and regained consciousness on 30 April 2006.<ref name=Medical/> He was later transferred to the [[military hospital]] at Army Headquarters and subsequently flown to [[Singapore]] for medical treatment.<ref name=reassumes>[http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20060731_09 General Sarath Fonseka reassumes the office], Ministry of Defence website, Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref> Years later, in 2016 Fonseka requested President [[Maithripala Sirisena]] to take steps towards releasing the person imprisoned in connection with his attempted assassination.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jayawardhane|first1=Kalathma|title=Release person imprisoned over my suicide attack: SF|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/107028/Release-person-imprisoned-over-my-suicide-attack-SF|publisher=Daily Mirror|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Eelam War IV===\nAfter recovering from his wounds, Lt. General Fonseka resumed his duties in July 2006.<ref name=reassumes/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4941744.stm|title=Bomb targets Sri Lanka army chief|publisher=BBC News|date=25 April 2006}}</ref> Fonseka has been described as the mastermind of the military [[strategy]] behind the military victory in Sri Lanka's three-decade war against terrorism.<ref name=Khaleej/><ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref name=Review/><ref name=24s>[http://www.island.lk/2009/06/08/news3.html Mi 24s role in eelam war IV emphasised] by Shamindra Ferdinando, [[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]], Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.nation.lk/2009/07/19/militarym.htm Refurbishing the Armed Forces] By Tissa Ravindra Perera, The Nation, Retrieved 18 May 2015</ref>  He abandoned conventional methods, matched the ingenious [[Military tactics|tactics]] and strategies of the LTTE, fully utilized the superior numerical strength and fire power of the Sri Lankan armed forces and kept up pressure on the enemy. He broke tradition by insisting on the full deployment of naval and air power to aid the war on land and succeeded in getting the support of the other service commanders.<ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/22/us-sri-lanka-fonseka-idUSKBN0MI0NQ20150322 Sri Lanka promotes former general who defeated Tigers to field marshal], by Shihar Aneez, [[Reuters]], Retrieved 31 March 2015</ref>\n\nFonseka broke army units into small groups and made these highly trained and motivated men who infiltrated Tiger-held areas, tracked down the fighting cadres of the LTTE and eliminated them.<ref name=early/><ref name=24s/> He transformed the Sri Lankan army from its defensive posture to an offence force.<ref name=Express/><ref name=\"Victory\"/> Along with his proactive military leadership, the battle-hardened commander changed military strategy in preparations before the war such as changing the training and ethos of the [[infantry]]<ref name=\"The Man of the Moment\"/><ref name=Innovations/><ref name=Analysis/> and preparing the defences in the north.<ref name=elevated/><ref name=Portal/><ref name=Guardian/><ref name=HSZ/> He empowered the frontline soldier, breaking the norms of conventional military attitude.<ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref name=Innovations/> In 2007, Fonseka introduced the [[Mechanized Infantry Regiment]].<ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=11939 Now Mechanized Infantry moves to ME hot spot] By Shamindra Ferdinando, [[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]], Retrieved 18 May 2015</ref><ref>[http://transcurrents.com/tamiliana/archives/593 Tigers Get Ready to Face the Mechanized Infantry of the Army in North] by D.B.S.Jeyaraj, transcurrents, Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080128_10 \"Innovation to Engage\" the Medal Awarding ceremony of the Mechanized Infantry Regiment], Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka), Retrieved 23 May 2015</ref>\n\nFonseka changed the reactionary nature of the Army and formulated a plan that would end the war in a time frame of three years.<ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=124949 SF denies claim of 40,000 civilian deaths in Vanni, says his men paid heavy price by not using heavy weapons] By Shamindra Ferdinando, [[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]], Retrieved 21 May 2015</ref> The aim was shifted from capturing ground to destroying the enemy.<ref name=Analysis/><ref name=untold>[http://www.ft.lk/2015/03/10/general-sarath-fonseka-reveals-untold-story-of-eelam-war-iv/  General Sarath Fonseka reveals untold story of Eelam War IV], By Malik Gunatilleke, [[Daily FT]], Retrieved 21 March 2015</ref> He reduced operations conducted along the main roads and expanded the [[battlefront]] in order to disperse the enemy manpower and firepower. To this end he devised the strategy of introducing large numbers of four-man teams to the theater of war, there by reducing military and civilian casualties through dispersion, stealth and precision in operations<ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref name=Innovations/><ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2008/20081208/world.htm#9 Lanka seeks India help to \u2018finish\u2019 LTTE faster], [[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]], Retrieved 15 June 2015</ref> and fought the war on multiple fronts.<ref name=Analysis/><ref name=untold/> He inaugurated the northern campaign before the conclusion of the eastern campaign, thereby making it difficult for political intrusion to halt the war.<ref>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/archive/20070708/spotlight.htm President's Tiger deal exposed] - Sonali Samarasinghe (The Sunday Leader) Retrieved 14-02-2016</ref><ref>[http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2016/02/07/sec04.asp The return of Emil Kanthan] - Manjula Fernando (Sunday Observer) Retrieved 14-02-2016</ref><ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/2005/11/29/stories/2005112906001700.htm Rajapakse invites LTTE leader for peace talks] - V.S. Sambandan (The Hindu) Retrieved 14-02-2016</ref><ref>[http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?artid=16433&catid=13 Colombo to continue to maintain CFA with LTTE] - TamilNet Retrieved 14-02-2016</ref><ref>[http://www.ft.lk/2015/01/06/opposition-speak-out-ahead-of-crucial-vote/ Opposition speak out ahead of crucial vote] - Dharisha Bastians (Daily FT) Retrieved 14-02-2016</ref>\n\nDefying the famous advice of Chinese General and military strategist [[Sun Tzu]], General Fonseka opted instead to attack the LTTE's strongest areas. The commander also opted for performance over seniority and selected officers with experience in the field.<ref name=\"The Man of the Moment\"/><ref name=untold/> He restructured the Army Intelligence Units which proved vital for the [[Sri Lanka Navy|Navy]] and the [[Sri Lanka Air Force|Air Force]] to destroy LTTE ships, commanders and other targets.<ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref name=untold/> Fonseka implemented strong measures to improve the discipline in the army, eradicate corruption and wastage. He also reduced the burden on the government and the citizen by the effective management of the resources at his disposal and personally ensured the unimpeded supply of ammunition.<ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref name=untold/><ref>[https://www.adaderana.lk/news/30254/fonseka-to-continue-in-politics-while-protecting-respect- Fonseka to continue in politics while protecting respect], adaderana.lk, Retrieved 15 June 2015</ref> In January 2009, he was described as the ''best army commander in the world'' by India's [[National Security Advisor (India)|National Security Advisor]].<ref name=hero/><ref name=early/><ref name=\"Victory\"/>\n\n;Defeat of the LTTE\n[[File:Sarath Fonseka at Ananda.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Fonseka in 2009]]\nOn 18 May 2009, the Sri Lankan military completely defeated the [[LTTE]] after 26 years of civil war.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090518_13|title='He Told the task accomplished'|publisher=Official government defence site}} Press Release, Ministry of Defence, Public Security, Law & Order.</ref> Fonseka played a key role as Commander of the Army, and is considered as a national hero by the majority of Sri Lankans due to this achievement.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/srilanka/7005269/Sri-Lankan-warrior-has-president-in-his-sights.html Sri Lankan warrior has president in his sights]. Telegraph (UK), Retrieved on 17 January 2010.</ref><ref name='economist-general'>{{cite news | title=General intentions | date=19 November 2009 |url =http://www.economist.com/world/asia/displaystory.cfm?story_id=14915330 |work=The Economist  | accessdate = 15 December 2009}}</ref> He was soon after promoted to [[General (Sri Lanka)|General]], becoming the becoming the first serving officer to hold a four star rank, since it was traditionally award to retiring Commanders of the Army.\n\n===Chief of Defence staff===\nFonseka was appointed Chief of Defence Staff (CDS) by President Rajapaksa effective 15 July 2009. He was the first person appointed CDS under the newly approved Chief of Defence Staff Act, which was supposed to give the CDS more responsibilities in co-ordinating the armed forces.<ref name=Defence/><ref>[http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Army-celebrates-60-years-as-bishop-of-Colombo-calls-for-peace-and-harmony-16537.html Army celebrates 60 years as bishop of Colombo calls for peace and harmony], by Melani Manel Perera, [[AsiaNews]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nFonseka officially handed over his letter of resignation to the President through the [[Gotabhaya Rajapaksa|Defence secretary]] on 12 November 2009. He requested to serve as CDS until the end of the month since he resigned to compete as a candidate for the presidential election which was held in January 2010. He left office on 16 November 2009,<ref>[http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=68019 Tribute to the fallen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091220094154/http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=68019 |date=20 December 2009 }}. Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka), Retrieved on 16 November 2009.</ref> President Mahinda Rajapaksa appointed Air Force Chief [[Roshan Goonatilake]] to succeed Fonseka on 16 November 2009.\n\n==Political career==\n===Post-war politics===\nThere were newspaper reports published about Fonseka entering politics after the war victory, beginning in August 2009. One of the articles explains it as follows, \"General Fonseka launches political campaign \u2013 I will make a supreme sacrifice to defend my land against the politicos who ever they may be joining hands with India. Now we have a daunting task to protect our motherland from India\".<ref>[http://www.lankanewspapers.com/news/2009/8/46939_space.html General Fonseka launches political campaign]. Lanka News Papers, Retrieved on 17 August 2009.</ref> Gen. Fonseka entering politics was a debate even during the war against LTTE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcurrents.com/tc/2008/12/post_125.html|title=Is Lt.Gen Sarath Fonseka nurturing a Political Ambition After Retirement?|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Presidential candidate===\nFonseka was installed as the common candidate by a coalition of political parties consisting mainly of the [[United National Party]] and the [[Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna]] and had the support of former president [[Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga]]. General Fonseka however declared himself as a non-party candidate.\n\nImmediately after declaration that Fonseka was ready for candidacy, President Rajapakse called for new presidential election two years before expiration of his term.<ref>{{cite news|title=President Rajapaksa calls for early election|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/president-rajapaksa-calls-for-early-election/545158/|newspaper=Indian Express|date=23 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nFonseka, UNP and JVP led a strong campaign against President Rajapakse. They claimed that Fonseka was the real hero who won the war against LTTE and a Fonseka government was ready for good governance along with the support of all the minorities, eliminate prevailing corruption under Mahinda Rajapaka government and also promised a massive salary increase for public servants which had been denied thus far. They also promised to change the constitution to remove executive powers from the presidency and transfer such powers to the parliament. Further they promised to establish the 17 amendment to authorise independent commissions as a measure to counter the ongoing mishandling of public money.<ref>[http://indi.ca/2010/01/sarath-fonsekas-election-manifesto/ Sarath Fonseka\u2019s Election Manifesto]. indi.ca (7 January 2010). Retrieved on 23 March 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=124612 SF vows to punish thieves of public funds], By Harischandra Gunaratna, The Island, Retrieved 15 June 2015</ref>\n[[File:Sarath Fonseka Posters.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Election campaign posters]]\nFonseka suffered a number of setbacks in his election campaign. In December 2009, A news item was published in local newspaper \"Sunday Leader\" quoting Sarath Fonseka saying that during the final few days of the war against LTTE, Defence Secretary Gotabaya Rajapakse (who is a brother of the President) gave orders to the army senior officers to execute three LTTE cadres who surrendered to the Army.<ref>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2009/12/13/%E2%80%9Cgota-ordered-them-to-be-shot%E2%80%9D-%E2%80%93-general-sarath-fonseka/ \u201cGota Ordered Them To Be Shot\u201d \u2013 General Sarath Fonseka | The Sunday Leader]. Thesundayleader.lk (13 December 2009). Retrieved on 23 March 2011.</ref> Due to the massive publicity given in the state media, this statement was taken by the whole country as betrayal of army officers by the retired army commander himself.<ref>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2010/01/24/rajapaksa-gets-astounding-98-of-time-on-state-media/ Rajapaksa Gets Astounding 98% Of Time On State Media | The Sunday Leader]. Thesundayleader.lk (24 January 2010). Retrieved on 23 March 2011.</ref> Although General Fonseka later issued a statement saying that his original statement has been published by the Sunday Leader out of context, many analysts say that Fonseka lost the election from that moment.<ref>http://lankainfoonline.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=32:fonseka-denies-sunday-leader-report&catid=3:news&Itemid=1</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, in the next attempt government put some evidence before public that General Fonseka was corrupt while he was the commander of the Sri Lanka Army. There was evidence that he removed the tender board chairman from the office and he himself became the chairman only to offer all the tenders to a company owned by his son-in-law. Adding fuel to the fire, one of his close friends living in Oklahoma USA \"Upul Illangamge\" spilled the beans<ref>{{cite news|title=Will expose arms deals \u2013 Ilangamge|url=http://www.lankanewspapers.com/news/2010/1/52597_space.html|newspaper=Lankannewspapers.com|date=12 January 2010}}</ref> by disclosing to the media in a press conference how the company was formed, registered in USA and Fonseka's son-in-law sold 3&nbsp;million rupees worth equipment necessary for the war during the final three years of the war. Fonseka claimed that the company referred in the accusation has no connection to his son-in-law's company although both companies share one name: Hicorp. But this allegation was on all public & state media supporting the government day and night and it had been used as a mean of discredit his reputation and attempts were also made to label him as a traitor by key spokespeople in the government.\n\nThen the Tamil National Alliance (TNA), a party loyal to LTTE, agreed to support Sarath Fonseka<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil National Alliance announced support for General Fonseka|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/tamil-national-alliance-announced-support-for-general-fonseka/article75898.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=9 January 2010|location=Chennai, India|first=B. Muralidhar|last=Reddy}}</ref> in the Presidential Election after having several discussions with both Mahinda Rajapakse and General Sarath Fonseka. Then government disclosed a secret agreement between TNA and General Fonseka<ref>{{cite news|title=Fonseka accused of making 'secret pact' with TNA|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/fonseka-accused-of-making-secret-pact-with-tna/article76689.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=7 January 2010|location=Chennai, India|first=B. Muralidhar|last=Reddy}}</ref> in which Fonseka had promised merger of North and East provinces and an autonomous status for Tamils in return for the support of the north and east Tamil population in the Presidential election. However opposition leaders proved that the agreement was a fake one with fake signatures adapted by another resources. But some Sinhalese reacted with anger to this agreement since the army fought 30-year-old bloody war against LTTE only to reject similar autonomous state \"Ealam\" claimed by the LTTE. Also the opposition revealed a secret written agreement between Mahinda Rajapaksa and EPDP Leader [[Douglas Devananda]] who was a Tamil politician faithful to Rajapakse.<ref>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2009/12/20/the-mahinda-rajapakse-douglas-devananda-agreement/ The Mahinda Rajapakse-Douglas Devananda Agreement: | The Sunday Leader]. Thesundayleader.lk (20 December 2009). Retrieved on 23 March 2011.</ref>\n\nSarath Fonseka however sincerely expected that he was set for a massive win on 26 January 2010. He booked 70 rooms of a five star hotel some hundred metres away from the President's House for the night of 26 January 2010. Medias citing Sri Lankan military reported that a large number (about 400) of deserted army soldiers spent the night with General Fonseka at the hotel to enjoy the election results. Fonseka camp stated that there may be about 400 people in the hotel but are the leaders of parties supporting the common opposition candidate, and did not consist of any army deserters.<ref>{{cite news|title=Army deserters at leading hotel|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/index.php/news/1226-army-deserters-at-leading-hotel.html|accessdate=20 October 2013|newspaper=Daily Mirror}}</ref>\n\nElection results were released by the election commissioner electorate by electorate in the morning of 27 January 2010.\n\n===Post Presidential Election 2010===\nSarath Fonseka refused to accept the election results published by the Election Commissioner.<ref>[http://www.lankatruth.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4580:we-do-not-accept-the-distorted-result-of-the-election-gen-fonseka&catid=35:local&Itemid=50 We do not accept the distorted result of the election \u2013 General Fonseka]. Lankatruth.com (28 January 2010). Retrieved on 23 March 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8482963.stm | work=BBC News | title=Sri Lanka poll victory challenged | date=27 January 2010 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> He also said he would consider legal action but did not indicate against whom. There are reports that say Sarath Fonseka is making every possible attempt to leave the country<ref>{{cite news|title=Beaten Sri Lankan general considers asylum in Australia|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-01-29/beaten-sri-lankan-general-considers-asylum-in/313520|accessdate=29 January 2010|newspaper=ABC News Australia}}</ref> as early as possible quoting him saying \"I cannot even leave the country, Rajapakse has blacklisted my passport along with my family, including my daughters' who are still studying in USA\". Some newspapers reported that he is seeking asylum in Australia, UK or India. Meanwhile, BBC announced that Gotabaya Rajapakse is intending to take legal action against Sarath Fonseka for leaking top secret government information. Later he stated in a press conference that he does not intend to leave the country, rather would stay with the people who voted him to see the justice is established.\n\nOn 28 January 2010 CID began its new investigations on claims made by several ministers of Rajapakse government that Fonseka was planning a coup to remove Rajapakse<ref>{{cite news|title=Gen Fonseka arrested, to be court martialled|url=http://www.timesnow.tv/Gen-Fonseka-arrested-to-be-court-martialled/articleshow/4338099.cms|date=9 February 2010|newspaper=Times Now}}</ref> in case of close election results on 26 January in connection with this investigation, a media institution \"Lanka\" run by JVP who helped Fonseka during presidential election was sealed on 30 January 2010 by the CID with a court order. Within few days the court accepted the appeal and ordered CID to re-open the office.<ref>{{cite news|title=CID seals 'Lanka' office premises|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/index.php/news/1303-cid-seals-lanka-office-premises.html|newspaper=Daily mirror|date=30 January 2010}}</ref> \nSri Lanka Army arrested Sarath Fonseka for committing military offences on 8 February 2010.\n\n===Arrest and sentence===\nIt was alleged that Fonseka became a political prisoner after running as a presidential candidate against President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]].<ref>{{cite news|title=9000 political prisoners including Sarath Fonseka 9000 political prisoners including Sarath Fonseka|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news.php?nid=11079|newspaper=Ada Derana}}</ref> He was arrested at his office in Colombo on 8 February 2010 by the [[military police]] as he was at the time in the army regular reserve following retirement,<ref name=Lion/><ref name=\"Ada Derana\">{{cite news|url=http://adaderana.lk/news.php?nid=7131|title=Fonseka to face Court Marshal: MCNS|date=9 February 2010|publisher=Ada Derana|accessdate=10 February 2010}}</ref> and taken into military custody. The military announced he would be [[court-martial]]ed for \"committing military offences\" during his time as Chief of Defense Staff.<ref>[http://www.dailymirror.lk/index.php/news/1518-general-fonseka-arrested.html \"General Fonseka arrested\"], ''Daily Mirror'', 8 February 2010</ref> The military stated that he would be charged according to the SL ARMY ACT, Section 57(1). The military tribunal in which the case was heard was challenged on multiple issues including the suitability and qualifications of the judges<ref>http://www.groundreport.com/World/General-Fonsekas-Lawyers-To-Challenge-His-Court-Ma/2919678</ref> and the hearing of the case during an official holiday period of lawyers (9&ndash;13 August 2010), and his lawyers were not present. Furthermore, because the witnesses were summoned during the aforementioned period, the lawyers of the accused never had a chance to interrogate the witnesses. Amidst all these issues, the panel of judges of General Court Martial which included Major General A.L.R. Weeratunga, Major General Lalith Wijetunga and Major General Bhatiya Jayatilleke found Fonseka guilty of the charges. Sentenced to 30 months after the court martial in 2010 convicted him of irregularities in army procurement. In August 2010, by proclamation from President Mahinda Rajapaksa as Commander-in-Chief of the armed forces, he was [[cashiered]] from the army, having been stripped of his rank, medals and decorations. His military pension was forfeited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/100815/News/nws_02.html|title=President ratifies stripping of Fonseka|website=www.sundaytimes.lk}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011 Fonseka was sentenced to three years in jail and fined Rs. 5000 in a two-one split verdict delivered in the white flag case with two judges finding him guilty on one of the charges while one of the judges acquitted him on all three charges.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-15787672 | work=BBC News | title=Sri Lanka's jailed ex-army chief Fonseka given new term | date=18 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/19/world/asia/sri-lanka-2nd-sentence-for-ex-general-sarath-fonseka.html | work=The New York Times | title=Sri Lanka: 2nd Sentence for Ex-General Sarath Fonseka | date=18 November 2011}}</ref><ref>http://www.dailymirror.lk/top-story/14839-sarath</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, he was acquitted by Judge Sunil Rajapaksa of the [[High Court of Sri Lanka|High Court of Colombo]] of fraud charges in the case known as the \"Hi-Corp Case\" upholding the objections raised by his Counsel that the charges in the High Court and the Court Martial were substantially the same and that he cannot be sentenced twice on the same offense. However one more case continued against him in respect of an allegation that he harbored deserters during the presidential election campaign.\n\n===General Election 2010===\nSarath Fonseka, Leader of [[Democratic National Alliance (Sri Lanka)|Democratic National Alliance]], obtained over 98,000 votes only in Colombo District. It is the 2nd highest individual vote obtaining percentage ever in the Election, 89.0%. His party was placed 3rd in the district with 110,683 votes (11.78%).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/parliamentary_elections/01Z.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130413141019/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/parliamentary_elections/01Z.html |archivedate=13 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> General Sarath Fonseka was a Member of the [[Parliament of Sri Lanka|Sri Lankan Parliament]], until he was sentenced to serve a two and half-year prison sentence which made him unable to continue his membership in the chamber according to the Sri Lankan Constitution. However, he requested the Court of Appeal to issue writs against the cashiering, prison sentence and removal from parliament. The petition on the prison sentence was rejected in December 2011 and he appealed to the Supreme Court in January 2012. <!--Other two petitions are still being heard in the Court of Appeal.-->\n\n===Post release===\nA midst local and international pressure president Mahinda Rajapaksa signed the order documents for the release of Fonseka during May 2012.<ref name=Express/><ref name=chief/><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18143907 | work=BBC News | title=Sri Lanka's Sarath Fonseka freed from prison | date=21 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/may/20/sri-lankan-president-releases-rival | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Jason | last=Burke | title=Sri Lankan president orders release of Sarath Fonseka | date=20 May 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://www.colombotelegraph.com/index.php/the-fonseka-agenda/ The Fonseka Agenda], Colombo Telegraph, Retrieved 15 June 2015</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, DNA MP [[Tiran Alles]] resigned from the post of Secretary of the Democratic National Party headed by Sarath Fonseka. Alles was in the media spotlight as he held several rounds of discussions with President Mahinda Rajapaksa to secure the release of Sarath Fonseka.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news.php?nid=19555|title=Tiran Alles resigns from DNP Secretary Post|website=www.adaderana.lk}}</ref>\nIn October 2012, National Bhikku Front and DNA called for a movement for abolition of the executive presidency under the joint leadership of UNP MP [[Karu Jayasuriya]] and Fonseka. Despite the fact that Jayasuriya requested the permission,<ref>http://www.ft.lk/2012/10/17/karu-writes-to-ranil-over-wc-decision-to-restrict-members-activism-with-united-bhikku-front/</ref> United National Party leadership ordered its members to boycott the rally which was scheduled to be held at Hyde Park Colombo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=63996|title=The Island|website=www.island.lk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=25787:hundreds-brave-rainly-weather-to-attend-fonseka-rally&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=547|title=Times Online - Daily Online Edition of The Sunday Times Sri Lanka|website=www.sundaytimes.lk}}</ref>\nAlso in the same month, party deputy leader [[Arjuna Ranatunga]] resigned from the party.<ref>http://www.ceylontoday.lk/16-16570-news-detail-mp-ranatunga-resigns-from-dp.html</ref><ref>http://www.dailymirror.lk/news/23354-arjuna-resigns-from-sfs-party.html</ref>\n\n===Presidential Election 2015===\nIn November 2012, party chairman Jayantha Ketagoda resigned from the position.<ref>http://www.mirror.lk/news/3171-ketagoda-too-to-leave-fonseka</ref> Fonseka extended his support to [[Maithripala Sirisena]] in the [[2015 Sri Lankan presidential election]]. Following his victory, President Sirisena gave Fonseka a complete [[Pardon|Presidential Pardon]] and acquitted of all charges on 22 January 2015, restoring his civic rights. The pardon restored his military rank and decorations as well as his pension. He also requested reinstatement of his parliamentary seat which was taken by a member of his party after he lost it due to his conviction.<ref>[http://www.itnnews.lk/?p=61298 Sarath Fonseka goes to Court seeking his Parliamentary seat]</ref><ref>[http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2015/01/25/fea02.asp It was the people who won \u2013 General Sarath Fonseka]\nby Ranil Wijayapala, Sunday Observer, Retrieved 15 June 2015</ref>\nFonseka joined the [[United National Party]] on 30 June 2016 and was appointed the chief organizer of Kalaniya seat of the party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/35874/minister-sarath-fonseka-obtains-unp-membership|title=Minister Sarath Fonseka obtains UNP membership|website=www.adaderana.lk}}</ref>\n\n====Promotion to Field Marshal====\nIn March 2015, it was announced that General Fonseka would be promoted to the newly created rank of [[Field Marshal (Sri Lanka)|Field Marshal]], which was carried out on 22 March 2015 by President [[Maithripala Sirisena]].<ref name=elevated/><ref>[http://www.army.lk/detailed.php?NewsId=9473 Field Marshal Fonseka Salutes Memories of Fallen War Heroes], army.lk, Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://documents.gov.lk/files/egz/2015/3/1906-51_E.pdf|title=Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===General Election 2015===\nField Marshal Fonseka, contested the [[2015 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2015 General Election]] from his [[Democratic National Alliance (Sri Lanka)|Democratic National Alliance]] from Colombo district, however he was not elected neither was his party able to secure a seat during the election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.domainmarket.com/buynow/sinhayanews.com|title=sinhayanews.com is available at DomainMarket.com|website=sinhayanews.com is available at DomainMarket.com}}</ref>\n\n===Joining the UNP===\nIn February 2016, Sarath Fonseka signed a collective agreement between the Democratic Party (DP) and the ruling United National Party (UNP). The MoU was signed by Fonseka as the leader of the Democratic Party and Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe as the UNP leader. The two leaders exchanged agreements for the Democratic Party to join the United National Front (UNF), the coalition led by the UNP.<ref name=Lion/><ref>{{cite news|title=Secret behind Fonseka\u2019s re-entry|url=http://www.ceylontoday.lk/42-117661-news-detail-secret-behind-fonsekas-re-entry.html|work=Ceylon Today|date=14 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Cabinet Minister (2016-2018)====\nOn 9 February 2016, he took the oath as a [[Member of Parliament]] for the seat vacated by the death of [[M. K. A. D. S. Gunawardana]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Fonseka takes oath as MP|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/34116/fonseka-takes-oath-as-mp|work=Ada Derrana|date=9 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Right on Field Marshal!|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/160214/columns/right-on-field-marshal-182838.html|work=Sunday Times|date=14 February 2016}}</ref> and on 25 February, he was appointed as Cabinet Minister of Regional Development by President Sirisena which he led till May 2018, when he was appointed Cabinet Minister of Wildlife and Sustainable Development.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sarath Fonseka sworn in as Cabinet Minister|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/96562/sarath-fonseka-sworn-in-as-cabinet-minister|date=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2018 Sri Lankan constitutional crisis]], he lost his ministerial post and was not reappointed by President Sirisena at the end of the crisis. During the crisis, Sirisena had claimed that the name of Fonseka had come up in the investigation of the CID but was suppressed.<ref>{{cite web |title=President says plot linked to Fonseka was game changer |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/181028/news/president-says-plot-linked-to-fonseka-was-game-changer-317875.html |website=The Sunday Times Sri Lanka |accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Proposed Minister of Law and Order====\nFollowing the [[2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings]], the UNP led by Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe requested President Sirisena to appoint Fonseka as [[Ministry of Law and Order (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Law and Order]]. President Sirisena turned down the request.<ref>[http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Minister-of-Law-and-Order---Prez-rejects-request-to-appoint-SF/108-166421 Minister of Law and Order - Prez rejects request to appoint SF]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSarath Fonseka is married to [[Anoma Fonseka|Anoma Indumathi Munasinghe]], daughter of D. J. and Eugine Munasinghe of [[Dematagoda]], and has two daughters Aparna and Apsara.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2007/10/07/spe02.asp|title=All for the love of a soldier|publisher=Sunday Observer|date=7 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn [[Awards and decorations of the military of Sri Lanka#Order of precedence|order of precedence]]:\n* [[File:Rana wickrama medal.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Rana Wickrama Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Rana sura medal.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Rana Sura Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya medal bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya]]\n* [[File:Uttama Seva ribbon bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Uttama Seva Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Desha Putra Sammanaya ribbon bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Desha Putra Sammanaya]]\n* [[File:Purna Bhumi Padakkama ribbon bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Purna Bhumi Padakkama]]\n* [[File:North and East Operations Medal ribbon bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[North and East Operations Medal]]\n* [[File:Riviresa Campaign Services Medal ribbon bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Riviresa Campaign Services Medal]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Eelam War IV]]\n* [[Sri Lankan civil war]]\n* [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)]]\n* [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of Defence Staff]]\n* [[White Flag case]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{reflist|group=N}}\n<!--Ref:Sinhala - http://www.rivira.lk/2009/06/07/vishesha4.htm-->\n<!--Ref:Sinhala Article by Mrs. Sarath Fonseka - http://www.rivira.lk/2009/05/31/vishesha3.htm-->\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|author=yes|wikt=no|v=no|b=no|n=Category:Sarath Fonseka}}\n<!--\nPlease keep this section brief and simple to navigate. Specific pages already fully referenced within the article do not need repeating here.\n-->\n\n===Official sites===\n* [http://www.gensarathfonseka.com/ General Fonseka's Official Website]\n* [http://www.hansaya.lk/english/home.html New Democratic Front Official Website]\n\n===News media===\n* [http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2007/10/07/spe02.asp All for the love of a soldier]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/sarathfonseka Picture Gallery]\n* [https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gpqpUulSfU3D3CKfaKP0hfnXMwAw Fonseka appointed new Chief of Defence Staff]\n\n===Audio===\n* [http://video.dailymirror.lk/videos/204/fonseka-spells-out-his-political-ambitions General Fonseka spells out his political ambitions]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091221163150/http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=71108 General Fonseka speaks about the \u201ccorrupt people]\n\n===Interactive===\n* [http://www.sundaytimes.lk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=19598:sarath-fonseka-timeline&catid=106:graphics&Itemid=612/ Timeline of Sarath Fonseka]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-mil}}\n{{Succession box\n| title  = [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]]\n| before = [[Shantha Kottegoda]]\n| after  = [[Jagath Jayasuriya]]| years=6 December 2005 \u2013 15 July 2009\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| title  = [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of Defence Staff]]\n| before = [[Donald Perera]]\n| after  = [[Roshan Goonatilake]]| years=2009&nbsp;\u2013 15 November 2009\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Sri Lankan Civil War}}\n{{Commanders of the Sri Lankan Army}}\n{{Members of 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the Sri Lankan Parliament from Colombo}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fonseka, Sarath}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan field marshals]]\n[[Category:Sinha Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2010 Sri Lankan presidential election]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Sri Lanka Army]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:People from Southern Province, Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Dharmasoka College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Ananda College]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Military Academy graduates]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Defence Studies]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|disambiguation|Sarath (disambiguation){{!}}Sarath}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{EngvarB |date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix  = [[The Honourable|Hon.]] [[Field Marshal (Sri Lanka)|Field Marshal]] \n| birth_name        = Gardihewa Sarath Chandralal Fonseka\n| honorific-suffix  = [[Rana Wickrama Padakkama|RWP]], [[Rana Sura Padakkama|RSP]], [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya|VSV]], [[Uttama Seva Padakkama|USP]], [[Member of Parliament|MP]], [[Royal College of Defence Studies|rcds]], [[Psc (British Army)|psc]]\n| native_name = {{lang|si|\u0dc3\u0dbb\u0dad\u0dca \u0dc6\u0ddc\u0db1\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dda\u0d9a\u0dcf}}\n| image             = Fonseka Press Conference.jpg\n| alt               =\n| caption           = <span style=\"font-size:88%\">Fonseka at a press conference</span>\n| office10          =  Leader of the [[Democratic Party (Sri Lanka)|Democratic Party]]\n| predecessor10     = '''Office Created'''\n| successor10       = '''Office Dissolved'''\n| term_start10      = 1 April 2013\n| term_end10        = 30 April 2016\n| office1           = Minister of Wildlife and Sustainable Development\n| president1        = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister1    = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start1       = 1 May 2018\n| term_end1         = 26 October 2018\n| predecessor1      = [[Ravindra Samaraweera]]\n| successor1        = \n| office2           = [[Ministry of Urban Development (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Regional Development]]\n| president2        = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister2    = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start2       = 25 February 2016\n| term_end2         = 26 October 2018\n| predecessor2      = '''Office Established'''\n| successor2        = \n| constituency_MP  = [[National List Member of Parliament|National List]]\n| parliament       = Sri Lanka\n| majority         = \n| predecessor      = M.K.A.D.S. Gunawardana\n| successor        = \n| term_start       = 9 February 2016\n| term_end         =\n| constituency_MP3  = [[Colombo Electoral District|Colombo District]]\n| parliament3       = Sri Lanka\n| majority3         = 98,456 Preferential Votes\n| predecessor3      = \n| successor3        = Jayantha Katagoda\n| term_start3       = 22 April 2010\n| term_end3         = 7 October 2010\n| office4           = [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of the Defence Staff]]\n| term_start4       = 15 July 2009\n| term_end4         = 30 November 2009\n| predecessor4      = [[Donald Perera]]\n| successor4        = [[Roshan Goonetileke]]\n| office5           = [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lanka Army]]\n| term_start5       = 6 December 2005\n| term_end5         = 15 July 2009\n| predecessor5      = [[Shantha Kottegoda]]\n| successor5        = [[Jagath Jayasuriya]]\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1950|12|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place       = [[Ambalangoda]], [[Southern Province, Sri Lanka|Southern Province]], [[Dominion of Ceylon]]<br/>(now [[Sri Lanka]])\n| nationality       = Sri Lankan\n| death_date        =\n| death_place       = \n| alma_mater        = Madawalalanda Maha Vidyalaya, Ampara <!-- Ref: http://www.lankatruth.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4235:general-fonseka-visits-his-first-school-in-ampara-meets-classmate&catid=35:local&Itemid=50 --> [[Dharmasoka College|Dharmasoka College, Ambalangoda]]<br />[[Ananda College|Ananda College, Colombo]]\n| party            = [[United National Party]] <br /> <small>(2016 - Present )</small> <br />[[Democratic Party (Sri Lanka)|Democratic Party]] <br /> <small>(2013 - 2016)</small> <br /> [[Democratic National Alliance (Sri Lanka)|Democratic National Alliance]] <br /> <small>(2010 - 2013)</small> <br /> [[New Democratic Front (Sri Lanka)|New Democratic Front]] <br /> <small> (2009\u20132010) </small><ref group=\"N\">Only for the 2010 Presidential Election</ref>\n| otherparty       = [[United National Front (Sri Lanka)|United National Front]] <br /> <small>(2016 - Present)</small>\n| relations        =\n| spouse           = [[Anoma Fonseka]]\n| children         = Aparna Fonseka<br />Apsara Fonseka\n| residence        =\n| occupation       = [[Politician]]<br/> [[Military Officer]]\n| signature        =\n| signature_alt    =\n| website          =\n| footnotes        =\n| allegiance       = {{flag|Sri Lanka}}\n| branch           = {{army|Sri Lanka}}\n| unit             = [[Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment]]\n| serviceyears     = 1970\u20132009,<br />2015\u2013Present{{efn|Sri Lankan military officers of [[five-star rank]] hold their rank for life, and are considered to be serving officers until their deaths.}}\n| rank             = [[File:Sri_Lanka-army-OF-10.svg|10px]] [[Field Marshal (Sri Lanka)|Field Marshal]] \n| battles          = [[Sri Lankan Civil War]],<br />[[1987\u201389 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|Insurrection 1987\u201389]]\n| commands         = [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Army]]<br />[[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of the Defence Staff]]\n| mawards          =\n {{plainlist |\n* [[File:Rana wickrama medal.svg|25px]] [[Rana Wickrama Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Rana sura medal.svg|25px]] [[Rana Sura Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya medal bar.svg|25px]] [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya]]\n* [[File:Uttama Seva ribbon bar.svg|25px]] [[Uttama Seva Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Desha Putra Sammanaya ribbon bar.svg|25px]] [[Desha Putra Sammanaya]]\n }}\n}}\n[[Field marshal (Sri Lanka)|Field Marshal]]  '''Gardihewa Sarath Chandralal Fonseka''', [[Rana Wickrama Padakkama|RWP]], [[Rana Sura Padakkama|RSP]], [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya|VSV]], [[Uttama Seva Padakkama|USP]], [[Member of Parliament|MP]], [[Royal College of Defence Studies|rcds]], [[Psc (British Army)|psc]] ({{lang-si|\u0d9c\u0dbb\u0dca\u0daf\u0dd2\u0dc4\u0dda\u0dc0\u0dcf \u0dc3\u0dbb\u0dad\u0dca \u0da0\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb\u0dbd\u0dcf\u0dbd\u0dca \u0dc6\u0ddc\u0db1\u0dca\u0dc3\u0dda\u0d9a\u0dcf}}, {{lang-ta|\u0b9a\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bcd \u0baa\u0bca\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bc7\u0b95\u0bbe}}; born 18 December 1950), commonly known as '''Sarath Fonseka''', is a [[Sri Lanka]]n politician and a military leader. He was the eighteenth [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of Sri Lankan Army]], and under his command the Sri Lankan Army ended the 26-year [[Sri Lankan Civil War]] in 2009, defeating the rebel [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]]; he thereafter briefly served as the [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of Defence Staff]].<ref name=Defence>[http://www.defence.lk/main_abt.asp?fname=CDS_General General G. S. C. Fonseka RWP RSP VSV USP rcds psc], Ministry of Defence, Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref> After retiring from the Army with the rank of General, he entered politics as the common opposition candidate in the [[2010 Sri Lankan presidential election|2010 presidential election]] contesting against President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]. Following his controversial defeat in the presidential election he was elected to Parliament in the general election that followed. Soon after he was made a political prisoner and lost his parliamentary seat.<ref name=hero>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/100919/News/nws_16.html Prosecuting and persecuting the war hero \u2013 General Fonseka], By Somar Wijayadasa, [[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/south-asia/Sarath-Fonseka-becomes-Lankas-first-field-marshal/articleshow/46656265.cms Sarath Fonseka becomes Lanka\u2019s first field marshal] - [[The Times of India]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=Khaleej>[http://www.khaleejtimes.com/mobile/inside.asp?xfile=/data/international/2015/March/international_March538.xml&section=international& Fonseka to become first Sri Lankan Field Marshal], [[Khaleej Times]] (UAE), Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref> Fonseka supported [[Maithripala Sirisena]] in the [[2015 Sri Lankan presidential election|2015 presidential election]] and following his victory, the newly appointed President Sirisena gave Fonseka a full pardon reinstating his civic rights, military rank and decorations. Later he was promoted to the newly created rank of [[Field Marshal (Sri Lanka)|Field Marshal]] on 22 March 2015 becoming the first [[Sri Lankan Army]] officer to be promoted to the rank.<ref name=elevated>[http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=Gen_GSC_Fonseka_elevated_to_the_rank_of_Field_Marshal_20150322_01 Gen. GSC Fonseka elevated to the rank of 'Field Marshal'], Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka), Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=Portal>[http://www.news.lk/news/sri-lanka/item/6710-sarath-fonseka-to-be-bestowed-with-field-marshal-title Sarath Fonseka to be bestowed with Field Marshal Title] NEWS.LK (The Official Government News Portal of Sri Lanka), Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=Express>[http://www.newindianexpress.com/world/General-Fonseka-Made-Field-Marshal/2015/03/22/article2725227.ece General Fonseka Made Field Marshal] - P.K.Balachandran, [[The Indian Express]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref>\n\nOn 9 February 2016 he was appointed to Parliament as a [[National List Member of Parliament|national list candidate]] and served in the [[Cabinet of Sri Lanka|Cabinet of Ministers]] from 2016 to 2018 as Minister of Regional Development and thereafter as Minister of Wildlife and Sustainable Development until the [[2018 Sri Lankan constitutional crisis]].\n\nFonseka had joined the Sri Lanka Army in 1970 and was commissioned as a [[second lieutenant]] in June 1971 and rose through the ranks while completing training stints across [[South Asia]] and in the [[United States]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. He saw extensive action throughout the 26-year civil war and over the years acquired a reputation as a tough battlefield commander and was often in the thick of the action in fighting against the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam|Tamil Tigers]], culminating in a term as Commander of the Army from 6 December 2005 \u2013 15 July 2009.<ref name=Frontline>[http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl1710/17100100.htm The taking of Elephant Pass], D.B.S. JEYARAJ [[Frontline (magazine)]], Volume 17 - Issue 10, May. 13 - 26, 2000, Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=early>[http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2009/06/21/sec20.asp Army Commander revisits early beginnings], Shanika SRIYANANDA, [[Sunday Observer (Sri Lanka)|Sunday Observer]], Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref name=\"FM1\">[http://www.army.lk/detailed.php?NewsId=9469 Nation Salutes War Veteran, General Sarath Fonseka (Retd) Conferring Field Marshal Rank], army.lk, Retrieved 25 March 2015</ref> As commander, he oversaw the [[Eelam War IV|final phase]] of the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]], which resulted in the total defeat of the militant [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]]. He also survived an assassination attempt when an LTTE suicide bomber attacked his motorcade in April 2006.<ref name=Sydney>[https://www.smh.com.au/news/world/sri-lankas-top-general-wounded-in-suicide-attack/2006/04/25/1145861341920.html Sri Lanka's top general wounded in suicide attack], [[The Sydney Morning Herald]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=Medical>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/archive/20060507/politics.htm Medical battle that saved the Army Commander] By Chinthaka Fernando, [[The Sunday Leader]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=Taught>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/05/22/AR2009052202033.html|title=Mia Bloom \u2013 What the Tigers Taught Al-Qaeda|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=24 May 2009 }}</ref> Following the end of the war Fonseka was promoted to a four star rank in the Sri Lanka Army, becoming the first serving officer to hold a four star rank.<ref name=ever>[http://news.lk/news/sri-lanka/item/6744-sarath-fonseka-promoted-sri-lanka-s-first-ever-field-marshal Sarath Fonseka promoted Sri Lanka's first ever Field Marshal], NEWS.LK (The Official Government News Portal of Sri Lanka), Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090518_16 Armed Force Commanders promoted to next higher ranks]. Ministry of Defence, Public Security, Law & Order, Retrieved on 18 May 2009</ref> He has been described as Sri Lanka's most successful army commander.<ref name=Khaleej/><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-30912331 Sri Lanka rehabilitates ex-army chief Sarath Fonseka], Charles Haviland, [[BBC News]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref name=\"Victory\">{{cite book|title=Lost Victory: The Rise & Fall of LTTE Supremo, V. Prabhakaran|author=Mehta, Maj. Gen. (Retd) Raj K.|pages=13, 118, 330\u2013338, 360\u20138, 377, 380, 401\u201311|publisher=Pentagon Press|isbn=978-8182744431}}</ref><ref name=Review>[http://asiantribune.com/news/2012/06/02/lalins-column-review-gota%E2%80%99s-war-final-revised Review - Gota\u2019s War -Final- revised] By Major General (Retired) Lalin Fernando, Asian Tribune, Retrieved 18 May 2015</ref>\n\nA few months after the defeat of the Tamil Tigers, Fonseka was appointed [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|\nChief of Defence Staff]] by President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]. While his new post was of a higher rank, Fonseka saw the move as an attempt to sideline him. Amid rumours of his desire to enter politics, he subsequently retired from the post on 16 November 2009.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8361862.stm|title=S Lanka army head leaves abruptly|last=Haviland|first=Charles|date=16 November 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC News November\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8356570.stm|title=Sri Lanka military chief resigns|date=12 November 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref> On 29 November 2009, Fonseka formally announced his candidature in the [[2010 Sri Lankan presidential election|2010 Sri Lankan Presidential Election]]. His candidacy was endorsed by the main opposition parties, and Fonseka became the main opposition candidate challenging President Rajapaksa. He campaigned under the sign of a swan, and the slogan ''Vishvasaniya Venasak'' (A Credible Change).\n\nFollowing his election defeat, Fonseka was arrested on 8 February 2010, and the government announced he would be [[court-martial]]ed for committing \"military offences\".<ref>[http://www.nationalsecurity.lk/fullnews.php?id=23456 Former Army Commander General Sarath Fonseka in military custody], Media Center for National Security</ref><ref name=Lion>[http://www.dailymirror.lk/105390/The-night-the-Ambalangoda-Lion-roared-defiance THE NIGHT THE AMBALANGODA LION ROARED DEFIANCE] - D.B.S. Jeyaraj (Daily Mirror) Retrieved 14 February 2016</ref> He was convicted for corrupt military supply deals and sentenced to three years in prison.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iNE2z6YPPccyYObraBkLB7jEVadg Sri Lanka jails ex-army chief Fonseka] AFP \u2013 17 September 2010</ref>\nAfter serving more than 2 years in prison, Fonseka was released amidst local and international pressure on 21 May 2012.<ref name=Express/><ref name=chief>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/mar/23/ex-army-chief-sarath-fonseka-jailed-for-treason-made-field-marshal-in-sri-lanka#img-1 Ex-army chief Sarath Fonseka, jailed for treason, made field marshal in Sri Lanka], [[The Guardian]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref> As per the pre-election statement, President [[Maithripala Sirisena]], gave him the Complete Presidential Pardon and acquitted him of all the charges against him on 22 January 2015, restoring his Civic Rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news.lk/news/business/item/5835-sarath-fonseka-acquitted-of-all-charges|title=Sarath Fonseka acquitted of all charges|website=www.news.lk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-30912331|title=Sri Lanka rehabilitates top general|date=21 January 2015|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nFonseka was born on 18 December 1950 in the coastal town of [[Ambalangoda]] in the south of Sri Lanka. His father was Peter Fonseka, a school principal and his mother Piyawathie Fonseka was a teacher. He initially attended Madawalalanda Maha Vidyalaya (1955\u20131957) in [[Ampara]],<ref>[http://www.lankatruth.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4235:general-fonseka-visits-his-first-school-in-ampara-meets-classmate&catid=35:local&Itemid=50 General Fonseka visits his first school in Ampara]. Lanka Truth, Retrieved on 7 January 2010.</ref> later receiving his secondary education from [[Dharmasoka College|Dharmasoka College, Ambalangoda]] (1958\u20131965) and [[Ananda College|Ananda College, Colombo]] (1966\u20131969). Fonseka represented his alma mater in [[National Cadet Corps (Sri Lanka)|cadeting]], swimming and [[water polo]] events. He was the college swimming and water polo captain in 1969 and later represented the [[Military of Sri Lanka|defence services]] and the country in these sports.<ref name=Defence/> He was a [[Sergeant]] of the [[National Cadet Corps (Sri Lanka)|College Cadet Platoon]].<ref>[http://archives.dailynews.lk/2009/07/03/Sup.asp?id=s13 Meteoric rise of Ananda's patriotic sons], Rasika SOMARATNA, [[Daily News (Sri Lanka)|Daily News]], Retrieved 4 May 2015</ref><ref name=inspires>[http://archives.dailynews.lk/2009/07/03/Sup.asp?id=s17 Ananda inspires students to serve the Nation], [[Daily News (Sri Lanka)|Daily News]], Retrieved 4 May 2015</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n===Early years===\nFonseka joined a [[Ceylon Army]] on 5 February 1970 as a [[cadet officer]] and after completing his basic officer training at the [[Sri Lanka Military Academy|Army Training Centre]] in [[Diyatalawa]], he was commissioned as a [[Second Lieutenant]] in the 1st Battalion, [[Ceylon Sinha Regiment]] on 1 June 1971 during the [[1971 Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna Insurrection|1971 Insurrection]].<ref name=\"FM1\"/>\n\nServing with as [[platoon commander]] in the Sinha Regiment, he was promoted to [[Lieutenant]] in 1973 and was promoted to the rank of [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]] in 1976. During this time he underwent the [[Commando]] Officers Course (1973), Battalion Support Weapons Course (1976) and Counter Insurgency Jungle Warfare Course (1978) in India. In 1980 he was promoted to the rank of [[Major]] and in 1981 he attend the Company Commanders Course in Pakistan. In the next few years he served as an [[Drill instructor|instructor]] at the [[Sri Lanka Military Academy]], Ampara Combat Training School and [[Infantry Training Centre (Sri Lanka Army)|Infantry Training Centre]], and later as the Chief Instructor and Deputy Commandant in the same training institutes.<ref name=\"FM1\"/>\n\n===Eelam War I===\nIn 1987, he graduated from [[Defence Services Command and Staff College (Bangladesh)|Defence Services Command and Staff College]], [[Mirpur Model Thana|Mirpur]] in Bangladesh. On his return was appointed [[Commanding Officer]], [[Sri Lanka Light Infantry|4th Sri Lanka Light Infantry]] and participated in the [[Vadamarachchi Operation]].[http://www.elakiri.com/forum/picture.php?albumid=1886&pictureid=7812]<ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/090628/Plus/sundaytimesplus_08.html Operation Liberation One], [[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)|The Sunday Times]], Retrieved 6 April 2015</ref><ref>[http://oaaj.org/speech.html Full text of H.E\u0081fs speech at the War Heroes commemoration event at the Ananda College], Old Anandians Web Japan, Retrieved 6 April 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090703_07 Sri Lanka taught world the art of humane ops-President], Ministry of Defence, Retrieved 6 April 2015</ref> The following year he was promoted to [[Lieutenant Colonel]] and appointed Commanding Officer, 1st Battalion, Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment in 1989.\n\nWith the on set of the [[1987\u201389 JVP Insurrection]], he was appointed as military coordinating officer for [[Gampaha District]].<ref name=\"FM1\"/> Fonseka reputedly devised the plan which led to the capture of [[Premakumar Gunaratnam]] and gained a reputation for his [[humane]] treatment of detainees.<ref>[http://www.dailymirror.lk/62597/fsp-leader-kumar-gunaratnam-fought-a-guerilla-war-against-the-indian-army FSP leader Kumar Gunaratnam fought a Guerilla war against the Indian army: Security Forces], By D.B.S.Jeyaraj, [[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref>\n\n===Eelam War II===\nIn 1991, he was promoted to [[Colonel]] and served as a [[brigade commander]], 3rd Brigade during [[Operation Balavegaya]] and distinguished himself as a Brigade Commander. In the [[First Battle of Elephant Pass]], the Sri Lankan armed forces were able to beat back the LTTE owing to the tenacity of the besieged troops led by Fonseka and the grit with which they held on despite the overwhelming odds.<ref name=Frontline/> Thereafter he was appointed as Center Commandant, Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment at [[Ambepussa]] and next served as Staff Officer I at the Directorate of Operations at the [[Army Headquarters, Colombo|Army Headquarters]].\n\nIn 1993, the [[Jaffna Fort]] was under siege by Tamil Tiger rebels. Then [[Colonel]] Fonseka led troops in the daring [[Midnight Express (military operation)|Midnight Express]] operation to relieve besieged troops. Several hundred soldiers were saved due to the operation. Colonel Fonseka was wounded that year in the Yaldevi operation, having been shot through the lung. At the time Fonseka was commanding the [[23 Division (Sri Lanka)|23 Division]]. After recovering, he was promoted to [[Brigadier]] in December 1993 and was appointed to the Operational Headquarters in Colombo.<ref name=\"FM1\"/>\n\n===Eelam War III===\n[[Brigadier]] Fonseka was soon deployed to operational areas serving as Commander - Area Headquarters, [[Mannar, Sri Lanka|Mannar]]; [[General Officer Commanding]], 5 Division in Mannar; General Officer Commanding, [[21 Division (Sri Lanka)|21 Division]]; Deputy Commander, Task Force I; General Officer Commanding, 3 Division in [[Batticaloa]]; General Officer Commanding, 27 Division in [[Kilinochchi]]; Coordinating Officer for [[Kayts]] and [[Mandattivu]], Deputy General Officer Commanding, [[51 Division (Sri Lanka)|51 Division]] in [[Jaffna]], General Officer Commanding, [[23 Division (Sri Lanka)|23 Division]] in [[Polonnaruwa]]; Overlooking General Officer Commanding [[Vavuniya]] Task Force - 2; General Officer Commanding, [[55 Division (Sri Lanka)|55 Division]] at [[Mirusuvil]].\n\nIn 1995 Brigadier Fonseka won widespread plaudits for his role in [[Operation Riviresa]] - the army's operation to capture Jaffna town from the Tamil Tigers.<ref name=inspires/> He played a major role in [[Operation Jayasikurui]].<ref name=\"FM1\"/> In 1998, he was promoted to the rank of [[Major General]]. He was appointed [[Colonel of the Regiment]] of the Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment. Serving as General Officer Commanding, [[22 Division (Sri Lanka)|22 Division]] and [[Director General]], [[General Staff]] at the Army Headquarters.\n\nIn 2000, with the imminent fall of [[Elephant Pass]], Major General Fonseka was rushed in as Commander, [[Security Forces Headquarters - Jaffna ]] and successfully defended the [[Jaffna peninsula]] from the massive offensive [[Operation Unceasing Waves III]] launched by the LTTE.<ref name=Frontline/><ref name=early/><ref name=Guardian>[http://www.slguardian.org/?p=15274 We built too many walls and not enough bridges], By Keerthi Ratnayaka, [[Sri Lanka Guardian]], Retrieved 31 March 2015</ref> Thereafter he served as Commander, [[Security Forces Headquarters - Wanni]]. From May 2002 to November 2003 after he was again appointed the Commander, Security Forces Headquarters  - Jaffna, Fonseka strengthened the defences of Jaffna<ref name=early/><ref name=inspires/><ref name=Guardian/><ref name=HSZ>[http://slwaronterror.blogspot.co.uk/2015/03/jaffna-hsz-reduced-further.html 2002-2003 controversy over Jaffna HSZ] by Shamindra Ferdinando, [[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]], Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.lankaweb.com/news/items03/160203-2.html LTTE DEMONSTRATIONS IN JAFFNA AND VAVUNIYA BURN EFFIGIES OF JAFFNA COMMANDER SARATH FONSEKA AND DEMAND ARMY TO QUIT], By Walter Jayawardhana, (LankaWeb), Retrieved 31 March 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.sundaytimes.lk/021229/columns/sitrep.html HSZ row: Story behind the story] The Sunday Times, Retrieved 24 February 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/countries/shrilanka/document/papers/MG_sarath.htm De-escalation Plan proposed by Security Forces Commander, Jaffna Peninsula, Maj. Gen. Sarath Fonseka, to Enable Re-settlement of Civilians in High Security Zones, December 20, 2002] South Asia Terrorism Portal, Retrieved 24 February 2016</ref> and launched a new training programme for the [[infantry]].<ref name=\"The Man of the Moment\">[http://businesstoday.lk/cover_page.php?issue=202#sthash.cqHoVGsC.dpuf The Man of the Moment : Lieutenant General Sarath Fonseka], Business Today, Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref name=Innovations>[http://www.benning.army.mil/infantry/magazine/issues/2013/May-June/Welch.html Infantry Innovations: Sri Lanka\u2019s Experience] by LTC (Retired) Ivan Welch, U.S. Army Infantry Magazine, Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref name=Analysis>[http://www.futuredirections.org.au/files/1266992558-FDIStrategicAnalysisPaper-12February2010.pdf Strategic Analysis of Sri Lankan Military\u2019s Counter-Insurgency Operations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328123409/http://futuredirections.org.au/files/1266992558-FDIStrategicAnalysisPaper-12February2010.pdf |date=28 March 2015 }}, Sergei DeSilva-Ranasinghe, Future Directions International, Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref>\n\nThereafter he attended the [[Royal College of Defence Studies]] in London and on his return he was appointed Commandant, [[Defence Services Command and Staff College]].<ref name=\"FM1\"/> In 2003, he was appointed Commandant, [[Sri Lanka Army Volunteer Force]] and in 2004 he was appointed Director Infantry, Deputy Chief of Staff and then [[Chief of Staff]] of the Sri Lanka Army. In December 2005 he was appointed Commander of the Army by president Mahinda  Rajapaksa and was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant General]]<ref name=\"The Man of the Moment\"/>\n\n;Suicide bomb attack\n{{See also|Chaminda Ruwan Yakandawala}}\n\nOn 25 April 2006, Lt. General Fonseka survived an LTTE suicide bomb attack on his unarmored [[staff car]] by a pregnant LTTE operative named Anoja Kugenthirarasah who infiltrated Army Headquarters by attending the regular maternity clinic provided for civilians at the military hospital.<ref name=Taught/><ref>[http://www.tamilguardian.com/article.asp?articleid=632 Fonseka still critical after suicide bomb attack], [[Tamil Guardian]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,501060508-1189385,00.html If This is Called Peace], [[Time Magazine]], Retrieved on 30 April 2006.</ref> Fonseka was gravely wounded in the attack along with his [[Aide-de-camp|ADC]]; while nine others, including members of his security detail were killed.<ref name=Sydney/> The General was rushed to the [[Colombo General Hospital]] within minutes. This had been possible because the attack took place next to the Army Hospital and therefore an ambulance was at hand. Fonseka was conscious upon admittance and had communicated with his officers and the doctors. The general, who was unconscious following emergency surgery, was put on a ventilator and regained consciousness on 30 April 2006.<ref name=Medical/> He was later transferred to the [[military hospital]] at Army Headquarters and subsequently flown to [[Singapore]] for medical treatment.<ref name=reassumes>[http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20060731_09 General Sarath Fonseka reassumes the office], Ministry of Defence website, Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref> Years later, in 2016 Fonseka requested President [[Maithripala Sirisena]] to take steps towards releasing the person imprisoned in connection with his attempted assassination.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jayawardhane|first1=Kalathma|title=Release person imprisoned over my suicide attack: SF|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/107028/Release-person-imprisoned-over-my-suicide-attack-SF|publisher=Daily Mirror|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Eelam War IV===\nAfter recovering from his wounds, Lt. General Fonseka resumed his duties in July 2006.<ref name=reassumes/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4941744.stm|title=Bomb targets Sri Lanka army chief|publisher=BBC News|date=25 April 2006}}</ref> Fonseka has been described as the mastermind of the military [[strategy]] behind the military victory in Sri Lanka's three-decade war against terrorism.<ref name=Khaleej/><ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref name=Review/><ref name=24s>[http://www.island.lk/2009/06/08/news3.html Mi 24s role in eelam war IV emphasised] by Shamindra Ferdinando, [[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]], Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.nation.lk/2009/07/19/militarym.htm Refurbishing the Armed Forces] By Tissa Ravindra Perera, The Nation, Retrieved 18 May 2015</ref>  He abandoned conventional methods, matched the ingenious [[Military tactics|tactics]] and strategies of the LTTE, fully utilized the superior numerical strength and fire power of the Sri Lankan armed forces and kept up pressure on the enemy. He broke tradition by insisting on the full deployment of naval and air power to aid the war on land and succeeded in getting the support of the other service commanders.<ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/22/us-sri-lanka-fonseka-idUSKBN0MI0NQ20150322 Sri Lanka promotes former general who defeated Tigers to field marshal], by Shihar Aneez, [[Reuters]], Retrieved 31 March 2015</ref>\n\nFonseka broke army units into small groups and made these highly trained and motivated men who infiltrated Tiger-held areas, tracked down the fighting cadres of the LTTE and eliminated them.<ref name=early/><ref name=24s/> He transformed the Sri Lankan army from its defensive posture to an offence force.<ref name=Express/><ref name=\"Victory\"/> Along with his proactive military leadership, the battle-hardened commander changed military strategy in preparations before the war such as changing the training and ethos of the [[infantry]]<ref name=\"The Man of the Moment\"/><ref name=Innovations/><ref name=Analysis/> and preparing the defences in the north.<ref name=elevated/><ref name=Portal/><ref name=Guardian/><ref name=HSZ/> He empowered the frontline soldier, breaking the norms of conventional military attitude.<ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref name=Innovations/> In 2007, Fonseka introduced the [[Mechanized Infantry Regiment]].<ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=11939 Now Mechanized Infantry moves to ME hot spot] By Shamindra Ferdinando, [[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]], Retrieved 18 May 2015</ref><ref>[http://transcurrents.com/tamiliana/archives/593 Tigers Get Ready to Face the Mechanized Infantry of the Army in North] by D.B.S.Jeyaraj, transcurrents, Retrieved 17 May 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080128_10 \"Innovation to Engage\" the Medal Awarding ceremony of the Mechanized Infantry Regiment], Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka), Retrieved 23 May 2015</ref>\n\nFonseka changed the reactionary nature of the Army and formulated a plan that would end the war in a time frame of three years.<ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=124949 SF denies claim of 40,000 civilian deaths in Vanni, says his men paid heavy price by not using heavy weapons] By Shamindra Ferdinando, [[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]], Retrieved 21 May 2015</ref> The aim was shifted from capturing ground to destroying the enemy.<ref name=Analysis/><ref name=untold>[http://www.ft.lk/2015/03/10/general-sarath-fonseka-reveals-untold-story-of-eelam-war-iv/  General Sarath Fonseka reveals untold story of Eelam War IV], By Malik Gunatilleke, [[Daily FT]], Retrieved 21 March 2015</ref> He reduced operations conducted along the main roads and expanded the [[battlefront]] in order to disperse the enemy manpower and firepower. To this end he devised the strategy of introducing large numbers of four-man teams to the theater of war, there by reducing military and civilian casualties through dispersion, stealth and precision in operations<ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref name=Innovations/><ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2008/20081208/world.htm#9 Lanka seeks India help to \u2018finish\u2019 LTTE faster], [[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]], Retrieved 15 June 2015</ref> and fought the war on multiple fronts.<ref name=Analysis/><ref name=untold/> He inaugurated the northern campaign before the conclusion of the eastern campaign, thereby making it difficult for political intrusion to halt the war.<ref>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/archive/20070708/spotlight.htm President's Tiger deal exposed] - Sonali Samarasinghe (The Sunday Leader) Retrieved 14-02-2016</ref><ref>[http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2016/02/07/sec04.asp The return of Emil Kanthan] - Manjula Fernando (Sunday Observer) Retrieved 14-02-2016</ref><ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/2005/11/29/stories/2005112906001700.htm Rajapakse invites LTTE leader for peace talks] - V.S. Sambandan (The Hindu) Retrieved 14-02-2016</ref><ref>[http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?artid=16433&catid=13 Colombo to continue to maintain CFA with LTTE] - TamilNet Retrieved 14-02-2016</ref><ref>[http://www.ft.lk/2015/01/06/opposition-speak-out-ahead-of-crucial-vote/ Opposition speak out ahead of crucial vote] - Dharisha Bastians (Daily FT) Retrieved 14-02-2016</ref>\n\nDefying the famous advice of Chinese General and military strategist [[Sun Tzu]], General Fonseka opted instead to attack the LTTE's strongest areas. The commander also opted for performance over seniority and selected officers with experience in the field.<ref name=\"The Man of the Moment\"/><ref name=untold/> He restructured the Army Intelligence Units which proved vital for the [[Sri Lanka Navy|Navy]] and the [[Sri Lanka Air Force|Air Force]] to destroy LTTE ships, commanders and other targets.<ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref name=untold/> Fonseka implemented strong measures to improve the discipline in the army, eradicate corruption and wastage. He also reduced the burden on the government and the citizen by the effective management of the resources at his disposal and personally ensured the unimpeded supply of ammunition.<ref name=\"Victory\"/><ref name=untold/><ref>[https://www.adaderana.lk/news/30254/fonseka-to-continue-in-politics-while-protecting-respect- Fonseka to continue in politics while protecting respect], adaderana.lk, Retrieved 15 June 2015</ref> In January 2009, he was described as the ''best army commander in the world'' by India's [[National Security Advisor (India)|National Security Advisor]].<ref name=hero/><ref name=early/><ref name=\"Victory\"/>\n\n;Defeat of the LTTE\n[[File:Sarath Fonseka at Ananda.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Fonseka in 2009]]\nOn 18 May 2009, the Sri Lankan military completely defeated the [[LTTE]] after 26 years of civil war.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090518_13|title='He Told the task accomplished'|publisher=Official government defence site}} Press Release, Ministry of Defence, Public Security, Law & Order.</ref> Fonseka played a key role as Commander of the Army, and is considered as a national hero by the majority of Sri Lankans due to this achievement.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/srilanka/7005269/Sri-Lankan-warrior-has-president-in-his-sights.html Sri Lankan warrior has president in his sights]. Telegraph (UK), Retrieved on 17 January 2010.</ref><ref name='economist-general'>{{cite news | title=General intentions | date=19 November 2009 |url =http://www.economist.com/world/asia/displaystory.cfm?story_id=14915330 |work=The Economist  | accessdate = 15 December 2009}}</ref> He was soon after promoted to [[General (Sri Lanka)|General]], becoming the becoming the first serving officer to hold a four star rank, since it was traditionally award to retiring Commanders of the Army.\n\n===Chief of Defence staff===\nFonseka was appointed Chief of Defence Staff (CDS) by President Rajapaksa effective 15 July 2009. He was the first person appointed CDS under the newly approved Chief of Defence Staff Act, which was supposed to give the CDS more responsibilities in co-ordinating the armed forces.<ref name=Defence/><ref>[http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Army-celebrates-60-years-as-bishop-of-Colombo-calls-for-peace-and-harmony-16537.html Army celebrates 60 years as bishop of Colombo calls for peace and harmony], by Melani Manel Perera, [[AsiaNews]], Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nFonseka officially handed over his letter of resignation to the President through the [[Gotabhaya Rajapaksa|Defence secretary]] on 12 November 2009. He requested to serve as CDS until the end of the month since he resigned to compete as a candidate for the presidential election which was held in January 2010. He left office on 16 November 2009,<ref>[http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=68019 Tribute to the fallen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091220094154/http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=68019 |date=20 December 2009 }}. Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka), Retrieved on 16 November 2009.</ref> President Mahinda Rajapaksa appointed Air Force Chief [[Roshan Goonatilake]] to succeed Fonseka on 16 November 2009.\n\n==Political career==\n===Post-war politics===\nThere were newspaper reports published about Fonseka entering politics after the war victory, beginning in August 2009. One of the articles explains it as follows, \"General Fonseka launches political campaign \u2013 I will make a supreme sacrifice to defend my land against the politicos who ever they may be joining hands with India. Now we have a daunting task to protect our motherland from India\".<ref>[http://www.lankanewspapers.com/news/2009/8/46939_space.html General Fonseka launches political campaign]. Lanka News Papers, Retrieved on 17 August 2009.</ref> Gen. Fonseka entering politics was a debate even during the war against LTTE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcurrents.com/tc/2008/12/post_125.html|title=Is Lt.Gen Sarath Fonseka nurturing a Political Ambition After Retirement?|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Presidential candidate===\nFonseka was installed as the common candidate by a coalition of political parties consisting mainly of the [[United National Party]] and the [[Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna]] and had the support of former president [[Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga]]. General Fonseka however declared himself as a non-party candidate.\n\nImmediately after declaration that Fonseka was ready for candidacy, President Rajapakse called for new presidential election two years before expiration of his term.<ref>{{cite news|title=President Rajapaksa calls for early election|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/president-rajapaksa-calls-for-early-election/545158/|newspaper=Indian Express|date=23 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nFonseka, UNP and JVP led a strong campaign against President Rajapakse. They claimed that Fonseka was the real hero who won the war against LTTE and a Fonseka government was ready for good governance along with the support of all the minorities, eliminate prevailing corruption under Mahinda Rajapaka government and also promised a massive salary increase for public servants which had been denied thus far. They also promised to change the constitution to remove executive powers from the presidency and transfer such powers to the parliament. Further they promised to establish the 17 amendment to authorise independent commissions as a measure to counter the ongoing mishandling of public money.<ref>[http://indi.ca/2010/01/sarath-fonsekas-election-manifesto/ Sarath Fonseka\u2019s Election Manifesto]. indi.ca (7 January 2010). Retrieved on 23 March 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=124612 SF vows to punish thieves of public funds], By Harischandra Gunaratna, The Island, Retrieved 15 June 2015</ref>\n[[File:Sarath Fonseka Posters.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Election campaign posters]]\nFonseka suffered a number of setbacks in his election campaign. In December 2009, A news item was published in local newspaper \"Sunday Leader\" quoting Sarath Fonseka saying that during the final few days of the war against LTTE, Defence Secretary Gotabaya Rajapakse (who is a brother of the President) gave orders to the army senior officers to execute three LTTE cadres who surrendered to the Army.<ref>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2009/12/13/%E2%80%9Cgota-ordered-them-to-be-shot%E2%80%9D-%E2%80%93-general-sarath-fonseka/ \u201cGota Ordered Them To Be Shot\u201d \u2013 General Sarath Fonseka | The Sunday Leader]. Thesundayleader.lk (13 December 2009). Retrieved on 23 March 2011.</ref> Due to the massive publicity given in the state media, this statement was taken by the whole country as betrayal of army officers by the retired army commander himself.<ref>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2010/01/24/rajapaksa-gets-astounding-98-of-time-on-state-media/ Rajapaksa Gets Astounding 98% Of Time On State Media | The Sunday Leader]. Thesundayleader.lk (24 January 2010). Retrieved on 23 March 2011.</ref> Although General Fonseka later issued a statement saying that his original statement has been published by the Sunday Leader out of context, many analysts say that Fonseka lost the election from that moment.<ref>http://lankainfoonline.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=32:fonseka-denies-sunday-leader-report&catid=3:news&Itemid=1</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, in the next attempt government put some evidence before public that General Fonseka was corrupt while he was the commander of the Sri Lanka Army. There was evidence that he removed the tender board chairman from the office and he himself became the chairman only to offer all the tenders to a company owned by his son-in-law. Adding fuel to the fire, one of his close friends living in Oklahoma USA \"Upul Illangamge\" spilled the beans<ref>{{cite news|title=Will expose arms deals \u2013 Ilangamge|url=http://www.lankanewspapers.com/news/2010/1/52597_space.html|newspaper=Lankannewspapers.com|date=12 January 2010}}</ref> by disclosing to the media in a press conference how the company was formed, registered in USA and Fonseka's son-in-law sold 3&nbsp;million rupees worth equipment necessary for the war during the final three years of the war. Fonseka claimed that the company referred in the accusation has no connection to his son-in-law's company although both companies share one name: Hicorp. But this allegation was on all public & state media supporting the government day and night and it had been used as a mean of discredit his reputation and attempts were also made to label him as a traitor by key spokespeople in the government.\n\nThen the Tamil National Alliance (TNA), a party loyal to LTTE, agreed to support Sarath Fonseka<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil National Alliance announced support for General Fonseka|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/tamil-national-alliance-announced-support-for-general-fonseka/article75898.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=9 January 2010|location=Chennai, India|first=B. Muralidhar|last=Reddy}}</ref> in the Presidential Election after having several discussions with both Mahinda Rajapakse and General Sarath Fonseka. Then government disclosed a secret agreement between TNA and General Fonseka<ref>{{cite news|title=Fonseka accused of making 'secret pact' with TNA|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/fonseka-accused-of-making-secret-pact-with-tna/article76689.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|date=7 January 2010|location=Chennai, India|first=B. Muralidhar|last=Reddy}}</ref> in which Fonseka had promised merger of North and East provinces and an autonomous status for Tamils in return for the support of the north and east Tamil population in the Presidential election. However opposition leaders proved that the agreement was a fake one with fake signatures adapted by another resources. But some Sinhalese reacted with anger to this agreement since the army fought 30-year-old bloody war against LTTE only to reject similar autonomous state \"Ealam\" claimed by the LTTE. Also the opposition revealed a secret written agreement between Mahinda Rajapaksa and EPDP Leader [[Douglas Devananda]] who was a Tamil politician faithful to Rajapakse.<ref>[http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2009/12/20/the-mahinda-rajapakse-douglas-devananda-agreement/ The Mahinda Rajapakse-Douglas Devananda Agreement: | The Sunday Leader]. Thesundayleader.lk (20 December 2009). Retrieved on 23 March 2011.</ref>\n\nSarath Fonseka however sincerely expected that he was set for a massive win on 26 January 2010. He booked 70 rooms of a five star hotel some hundred metres away from the President's House for the night of 26 January 2010. Medias citing Sri Lankan military reported that a large number (about 400) of deserted army soldiers spent the night with General Fonseka at the hotel to enjoy the election results. Fonseka camp stated that there may be about 400 people in the hotel but are the leaders of parties supporting the common opposition candidate, and did not consist of any army deserters.<ref>{{cite news|title=Army deserters at leading hotel|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/index.php/news/1226-army-deserters-at-leading-hotel.html|accessdate=20 October 2013|newspaper=Daily Mirror}}</ref>\n\nElection results were released by the election commissioner electorate by electorate in the morning of 27 January 2010.\n\n===Post Presidential Election 2010===\nSarath Fonseka refused to accept the election results published by the Election Commissioner.<ref>[http://www.lankatruth.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4580:we-do-not-accept-the-distorted-result-of-the-election-gen-fonseka&catid=35:local&Itemid=50 We do not accept the distorted result of the election \u2013 General Fonseka]. Lankatruth.com (28 January 2010). Retrieved on 23 March 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8482963.stm | work=BBC News | title=Sri Lanka poll victory challenged | date=27 January 2010 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> He also said he would consider legal action but did not indicate against whom. There are reports that say Sarath Fonseka is making every possible attempt to leave the country<ref>{{cite news|title=Beaten Sri Lankan general considers asylum in Australia|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-01-29/beaten-sri-lankan-general-considers-asylum-in/313520|accessdate=29 January 2010|newspaper=ABC News Australia}}</ref> as early as possible quoting him saying \"I cannot even leave the country, Rajapakse has blacklisted my passport along with my family, including my daughters' who are still studying in USA\". Some newspapers reported that he is seeking asylum in Australia, UK or India. Meanwhile, BBC announced that Gotabaya Rajapakse is intending to take legal action against Sarath Fonseka for leaking top secret government information. Later he stated in a press conference that he does not intend to leave the country, rather would stay with the people who voted him to see the justice is established.\n\nOn 28 January 2010 CID began its new investigations on claims made by several ministers of Rajapakse government that Fonseka was planning a coup to remove Rajapakse<ref>{{cite news|title=Gen Fonseka arrested, to be court martialled|url=http://www.timesnow.tv/Gen-Fonseka-arrested-to-be-court-martialled/articleshow/4338099.cms|date=9 February 2010|newspaper=Times Now}}</ref> in case of close election results on 26 January in connection with this investigation, a media institution \"Lanka\" run by JVP who helped Fonseka during presidential election was sealed on 30 January 2010 by the CID with a court order. Within few days the court accepted the appeal and ordered CID to re-open the office.<ref>{{cite news|title=CID seals 'Lanka' office premises|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/index.php/news/1303-cid-seals-lanka-office-premises.html|newspaper=Daily mirror|date=30 January 2010}}</ref> \nSri Lanka Army arrested Sarath Fonseka for committing military offences on 8 February 2010.\n\n===Arrest and sentence===\nIt was alleged that Fonseka became a political prisoner after running as a presidential candidate against President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]].<ref>{{cite news|title=9000 political prisoners including Sarath Fonseka 9000 political prisoners including Sarath Fonseka|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news.php?nid=11079|newspaper=Ada Derana}}</ref> He was arrested at his office in Colombo on 8 February 2010 by the [[military police]] as he was at the time in the army regular reserve following retirement,<ref name=Lion/><ref name=\"Ada Derana\">{{cite news|url=http://adaderana.lk/news.php?nid=7131|title=Fonseka to face Court Marshal: MCNS|date=9 February 2010|publisher=Ada Derana|accessdate=10 February 2010}}</ref> and taken into military custody. The military announced he would be [[court-martial]]ed for \"committing military offences\" during his time as Chief of Defense Staff.<ref>[http://www.dailymirror.lk/index.php/news/1518-general-fonseka-arrested.html \"General Fonseka arrested\"], ''Daily Mirror'', 8 February 2010</ref> The military stated that he would be charged according to the SL ARMY ACT, Section 57(1). The military tribunal in which the case was heard was challenged on multiple issues including the suitability and qualifications of the judges<ref>http://www.groundreport.com/World/General-Fonsekas-Lawyers-To-Challenge-His-Court-Ma/2919678</ref> and the hearing of the case during an official holiday period of lawyers (9&ndash;13 August 2010), and his lawyers were not present. Furthermore, because the witnesses were summoned during the aforementioned period, the lawyers of the accused never had a chance to interrogate the witnesses. Amidst all these issues, the panel of judges of General Court Martial which included Major General A.L.R. Weeratunga, Major General Lalith Wijetunga and Major General Bhatiya Jayatilleke found Fonseka guilty of the charges. Sentenced to 30 months after the court martial in 2010 convicted him of irregularities in army procurement. In August 2010, by proclamation from President Mahinda Rajapaksa as Commander-in-Chief of the armed forces, he was [[cashiered]] from the army, having been stripped of his rank, medals and decorations. His military pension was forfeited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/100815/News/nws_02.html|title=President ratifies stripping of Fonseka|website=www.sundaytimes.lk}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011 Fonseka was sentenced to three years in jail and fined Rs. 5000 in a two-one split verdict delivered in the white flag case with two judges finding him guilty on one of the charges while one of the judges acquitted him on all three charges.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-15787672 | work=BBC News | title=Sri Lanka's jailed ex-army chief Fonseka given new term | date=18 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/19/world/asia/sri-lanka-2nd-sentence-for-ex-general-sarath-fonseka.html | work=The New York Times | title=Sri Lanka: 2nd Sentence for Ex-General Sarath Fonseka | date=18 November 2011}}</ref><ref>http://www.dailymirror.lk/top-story/14839-sarath</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, he was acquitted by Judge Sunil Rajapaksa of the [[High Court of Sri Lanka|High Court of Colombo]] of fraud charges in the case known as the \"Hi-Corp Case\" upholding the objections raised by his Counsel that the charges in the High Court and the Court Martial were substantially the same and that he cannot be sentenced twice on the same offense. However one more case continued against him in respect of an allegation that he harbored deserters during the presidential election campaign.\n\n===General Election 2010===\nSarath Fonseka, Leader of [[Democratic National Alliance (Sri Lanka)|Democratic National Alliance]], obtained over 98,000 votes only in Colombo District. It is the 2nd highest individual vote obtaining percentage ever in the Election, 89.0%. His party was placed 3rd in the district with 110,683 votes (11.78%).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/parliamentary_elections/01Z.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130413141019/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/parliamentary_elections/01Z.html |archivedate=13 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> General Sarath Fonseka was a Member of the [[Parliament of Sri Lanka|Sri Lankan Parliament]], until he was sentenced to serve a two and half-year prison sentence which made him unable to continue his membership in the chamber according to the Sri Lankan Constitution. However, he requested the Court of Appeal to issue writs against the cashiering, prison sentence and removal from parliament. The petition on the prison sentence was rejected in December 2011 and he appealed to the Supreme Court in January 2012. <!--Other two petitions are still being heard in the Court of Appeal.-->\n\n===Post release===\nA midst local and international pressure president Mahinda Rajapaksa signed the order documents for the release of Fonseka during May 2012.<ref name=Express/><ref name=chief/><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18143907 | work=BBC News | title=Sri Lanka's Sarath Fonseka freed from prison | date=21 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/may/20/sri-lankan-president-releases-rival | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Jason | last=Burke | title=Sri Lankan president orders release of Sarath Fonseka | date=20 May 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://www.colombotelegraph.com/index.php/the-fonseka-agenda/ The Fonseka Agenda], Colombo Telegraph, Retrieved 15 June 2015</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, DNA MP [[Tiran Alles]] resigned from the post of Secretary of the Democratic National Party headed by Sarath Fonseka. Alles was in the media spotlight as he held several rounds of discussions with President Mahinda Rajapaksa to secure the release of Sarath Fonseka.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news.php?nid=19555|title=Tiran Alles resigns from DNP Secretary Post|website=www.adaderana.lk}}</ref>\nIn October 2012, National Bhikku Front and DNA called for a movement for abolition of the executive presidency under the joint leadership of UNP MP [[Karu Jayasuriya]] and Fonseka. Despite the fact that Jayasuriya requested the permission,<ref>http://www.ft.lk/2012/10/17/karu-writes-to-ranil-over-wc-decision-to-restrict-members-activism-with-united-bhikku-front/</ref> United National Party leadership ordered its members to boycott the rally which was scheduled to be held at Hyde Park Colombo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=63996|title=The Island|website=www.island.lk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=25787:hundreds-brave-rainly-weather-to-attend-fonseka-rally&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=547|title=Times Online - Daily Online Edition of The Sunday Times Sri Lanka|website=www.sundaytimes.lk}}</ref>\nAlso in the same month, party deputy leader [[Arjuna Ranatunga]] resigned from the party.<ref>http://www.ceylontoday.lk/16-16570-news-detail-mp-ranatunga-resigns-from-dp.html</ref><ref>http://www.dailymirror.lk/news/23354-arjuna-resigns-from-sfs-party.html</ref>\n\n===Presidential Election 2015===\nIn November 2012, party chairman Jayantha Ketagoda resigned from the position.<ref>http://www.mirror.lk/news/3171-ketagoda-too-to-leave-fonseka</ref> Fonseka extended his support to [[Maithripala Sirisena]] in the [[2015 Sri Lankan presidential election]]. Following his victory, President Sirisena gave Fonseka a complete [[Pardon|Presidential Pardon]] and acquitted of all charges on 22 January 2015, restoring his civic rights. The pardon restored his military rank and decorations as well as his pension. He also requested reinstatement of his parliamentary seat which was taken by a member of his party after he lost it due to his conviction.<ref>[http://www.itnnews.lk/?p=61298 Sarath Fonseka goes to Court seeking his Parliamentary seat]</ref><ref>[http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2015/01/25/fea02.asp It was the people who won \u2013 General Sarath Fonseka]\nby Ranil Wijayapala, Sunday Observer, Retrieved 15 June 2015</ref>\nFonseka joined the [[United National Party]] on 30 June 2016 and was appointed the chief organizer of Kalaniya seat of the party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/35874/minister-sarath-fonseka-obtains-unp-membership|title=Minister Sarath Fonseka obtains UNP membership|website=www.adaderana.lk}}</ref>\n\n====Promotion to Field Marshal====\nIn March 2015, it was announced that General Fonseka would be promoted to the newly created rank of [[Field Marshal (Sri Lanka)|Field Marshal]], which was carried out on 22 March 2015 by President [[Maithripala Sirisena]].<ref name=elevated/><ref>[http://www.army.lk/detailed.php?NewsId=9473 Field Marshal Fonseka Salutes Memories of Fallen War Heroes], army.lk, Retrieved 29 March 2015</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://documents.gov.lk/files/egz/2015/3/1906-51_E.pdf|title=Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===General Election 2015===\nField Marshal Fonseka, contested the [[2015 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2015 General Election]] from his [[Democratic National Alliance (Sri Lanka)|Democratic National Alliance]] from Colombo district, however he was not elected neither was his party able to secure a seat during the election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.domainmarket.com/buynow/sinhayanews.com|title=sinhayanews.com is available at DomainMarket.com|website=sinhayanews.com is available at DomainMarket.com}}</ref>\n\n===Joining the UNP===\nIn February 2016, Sarath Fonseka signed a collective agreement between the Democratic Party (DP) and the ruling United National Party (UNP). The MoU was signed by Fonseka as the leader of the Democratic Party and Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe as the UNP leader. The two leaders exchanged agreements for the Democratic Party to join the United National Front (UNF), the coalition led by the UNP.<ref name=Lion/><ref>{{cite news|title=Secret behind Fonseka\u2019s re-entry|url=http://www.ceylontoday.lk/42-117661-news-detail-secret-behind-fonsekas-re-entry.html|work=Ceylon Today|date=14 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Cabinet Minister (2016-2018)====\nOn 9 February 2016, he took the oath as a [[Member of Parliament]] for the seat vacated by the death of [[M. K. A. D. S. Gunawardana]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Fonseka takes oath as MP|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/34116/fonseka-takes-oath-as-mp|work=Ada Derrana|date=9 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Right on Field Marshal!|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/160214/columns/right-on-field-marshal-182838.html|work=Sunday Times|date=14 February 2016}}</ref> and on 25 February, he was appointed as Cabinet Minister of Regional Development by President Sirisena which he led till May 2018, when he was appointed Cabinet Minister of Wildlife and Sustainable Development.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sarath Fonseka sworn in as Cabinet Minister|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/96562/sarath-fonseka-sworn-in-as-cabinet-minister|date=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2018 Sri Lankan constitutional crisis]], he lost his ministerial post and was not reappointed by President Sirisena at the end of the crisis. During the crisis, Sirisena had claimed that the name of Fonseka had come up in the investigation of the CID but was suppressed.<ref>{{cite web |title=President says plot linked to Fonseka was game changer |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/181028/news/president-says-plot-linked-to-fonseka-was-game-changer-317875.html |website=The Sunday Times Sri Lanka |accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Proposed Minister of Law and Order====\nFollowing the [[2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings]], the UNP led by Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe requested President Sirisena to appoint Fonseka as [[Ministry of Law and Order (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Law and Order]]. President Sirisena turned down the request.<ref>[http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Minister-of-Law-and-Order---Prez-rejects-request-to-appoint-SF/108-166421 Minister of Law and Order - Prez rejects request to appoint SF]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSarath Fonseka is married to [[Anoma Fonseka|Anoma Indumathi Munasinghe]], daughter of D. J. and Eugine Munasinghe of [[Dematagoda]], and has two daughters Aparna and Apsara.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2007/10/07/spe02.asp|title=All for the love of a soldier|publisher=Sunday Observer|date=7 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn [[Awards and decorations of the military of Sri Lanka#Order of precedence|order of precedence]]:\n* [[File:Rana wickrama medal.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Rana Wickrama Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Rana sura medal.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Rana Sura Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya medal bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya]]\n* [[File:Uttama Seva ribbon bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Uttama Seva Padakkama]]\n* [[File:Desha Putra Sammanaya ribbon bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Desha Putra Sammanaya]]\n* [[File:Purna Bhumi Padakkama ribbon bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Purna Bhumi Padakkama]]\n* [[File:North and East Operations Medal ribbon bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[North and East Operations Medal]]\n* [[File:Riviresa Campaign Services Medal ribbon bar.svg|60px]]&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Riviresa Campaign Services Medal]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Eelam War IV]]\n* [[Sri Lankan civil war]]\n* [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)]]\n* [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of Defence Staff]]\n* [[White Flag case]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{reflist|group=N}}\n<!--Ref:Sinhala - http://www.rivira.lk/2009/06/07/vishesha4.htm-->\n<!--Ref:Sinhala Article by Mrs. Sarath Fonseka - http://www.rivira.lk/2009/05/31/vishesha3.htm-->\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|author=yes|wikt=no|v=no|b=no|n=Category:Sarath Fonseka}}\n<!--\nPlease keep this section brief and simple to navigate. Specific pages already fully referenced within the article do not need repeating here.\n-->\n\n===Official sites===\n* [http://www.gensarathfonseka.com/ General Fonseka's Official Website]\n* [http://www.hansaya.lk/english/home.html New Democratic Front Official Website]\n\n===News media===\n* [http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2007/10/07/spe02.asp All for the love of a soldier]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/sarathfonseka Picture Gallery]\n* [https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gpqpUulSfU3D3CKfaKP0hfnXMwAw Fonseka appointed new Chief of Defence Staff]\n\n===Audio===\n* [http://video.dailymirror.lk/videos/204/fonseka-spells-out-his-political-ambitions General Fonseka spells out his political ambitions]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091221163150/http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=71108 General Fonseka speaks about the \u201ccorrupt people]\n\n===Interactive===\n* [http://www.sundaytimes.lk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=19598:sarath-fonseka-timeline&catid=106:graphics&Itemid=612/ Timeline of Sarath Fonseka]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-mil}}\n{{Succession box\n| title  = [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]]\n| before = [[Shantha Kottegoda]]\n| after  = [[Jagath Jayasuriya]]| years=6 December 2005 \u2013 15 July 2009\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| title  = [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of Defence Staff]]\n| before = [[Donald Perera]]\n| after  = [[Roshan Goonatilake]]| years=2009&nbsp;\u2013 15 November 2009\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Sri Lankan Civil War}}\n{{Commanders of the Sri Lankan Army}}\n{{Members of 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the Sri Lankan Parliament from Colombo}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fonseka, Sarath}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan field marshals]]\n[[Category:Sinha Regiment officers]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2010 Sri Lankan presidential election]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Sri Lanka Army]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:People from Southern Province, Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Dharmasoka College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Ananda College]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Military Academy graduates]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Defence Studies]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Dan arndt", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove flagicon from infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarath_Fonseka"}
{"title_page": "Genshin Impact", "text_new": "{{Undisclosed paid|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| collapsible = \n| state = \n| italic title = \n| title = Genshin Impact\n| image = Genshin_Logo.png\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| developer = miHoYo\n| publisher = \n| series = \n| engine = Unity\n| platforms = [[PlayStation 4]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = Spring 2020\n| genre = [[Action role-playing video game|Action role-playing]]\n| modes = \n| director = \n| producer = \n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = \n| writer = \n| composer = \n| cabinet = \n| arcade system = \n| cpu = \n| sound = \n| display = \n}}\n'''Genshin Impact''' is an upcoming [[open-world]] [[Action role-playing game|action role-playing video game]] developed by miHoYo. It is the second game from miHoYo to feature original IP (the first being Gun GirlZ).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mihayo.com/game.html|title=\u7c73\u54c8\u6e38-TECH OTAKUS SAVE THE WORLD|website=www.mihayo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Genshin Impact'' was announced in June 2019, with a release target of spring 2020, on both Windows and iOS - the reveal trailer showed an open world heavily inspired by ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]]'' in terms of presentation and gameplay. A [[beta test]] was to be run at the end of June.<ref>{{citation| url = https://gamerant.com/genshin-impact-game-zelda/ | title = Zelda-Inspired Open World Action Game 'Genshin Impact' Announced | first = Rory | last = Young | date = 8 June 2019 | work = gamerant.com }}</ref><ref>{{citation|  url = https://www.polygon.com/2019/6/21/18700922/genshin-impact-gameplay-beta-breath-of-the-wild-clone-botw | title = That Breath of the Wild anime \u2018clone\u2019 actually looks impressive | first = Patricia | last = Herndandez | date = 21 June 2019 | work = www.polygon.com }}</ref>\n\nAt Sony's ChinaJoy 2019 event the game was announced as also being published for [[PlayStation 4]].<ref>{{citation| url = https://gematsu.com/2019/08/genshin-impact-coming-to-ps4-in-2020 | title = Genshin Impact coming to PS4 in 2020 | first = Sal | last = Romano | date = 1 Aug 2019 | work = gematsu.com }}</ref> A [[Nintendo Switch]] version was announced on January 13, 2020 via press release.\n\n== Setting ==\nIn a world called Teyvat, certain individuals chosen by the gods are given a Vision \u2014 magical gemstones that give their bearers the ability to control an element. The player starts out as a Traveler of unknown origin who is searching for a lost sibling. The player can choose between a male or female version of the Traveler. As the adventure progresses, the player controls several other characters met by the Traveler on their journey, each with unique personalities and special abilities, as they undertake quests to understand the truth about the primordial gods of this world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\nThe game features an open-world map, which the player explores by walking, climbing, swimming and gliding as necessary. Many objects and places of significance are spread throughout the map.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gnn.gamer.com.tw/detail.php?sn=180824|title=\u300a\u5d29\u58de 3rd\u300b\u958b\u767c\u5546\u958b\u653e\u4e16\u754c\u5192\u96aa\u65b0\u4f5c\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u66dd\u5149 \u540c\u6b65\u516c\u958b\u9996\u652f\u9810\u544a\u5f71\u7247|website=\u5df4\u54c8\u59c6\u7279\u96fb\u73a9\u8cc7\u8a0a\u7ad9|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Players can control up to four of their characters at any one time. By completing quests to advance the story, the player is able to unlock a total of 30 playable characters.\n\nEach character has two unique combat skills: a normal and a special skill. The normal skill can be used at any time except for the cooldown period immediately after use, while the special skill has an energy cost, requiring the user to amass sufficient elemental energy first.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shouyou.gamersky.com/review/201906/1196056_2.shtml|title=\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u6d4b\u8bd5\u7248\u8bd5\u73a9\uff1a\u56fd\u4ea7\u624b\u6e38\u79bb3A\u6700\u8fd1\u7684\u4e00\u6b21 _ \u6e38\u6c11\u661f\u7a7a\u624b\u6e38\u9891\u9053|website=shouyou.gamersky.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Genshinimpact/|title=Genshin Impact|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nCooking is another significant aspect of Genshin Impact's gameplay. Players gather many resources in the course of their adventure, some of which can be turned into dishes via cooking. Some dishes regenerate characters' health, while others boost attack or defensive abilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shouyou.gamersky.com/review/201906/1196056_3.shtml|title=\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u6d4b\u8bd5\u7248\u8bd5\u73a9\uff1a\u56fd\u4ea7\u624b\u6e38\u79bb3A\u6700\u8fd1\u7684\u4e00\u6b21 _ \u6e38\u6c11\u661f\u7a7a\u624b\u6e38\u9891\u9053|website=shouyou.gamersky.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nmiHoYo announced work on a new project using the Unity development platform at the end of January 2017, three months after the initial release of Honkai Impact 3rd. The company stated its intention for the new project was to strengthen the company's R&D capabilities and produce higher-quality games. The project in question was Genshin Impact.\n\nThe game's developers have cited The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild and the Grand Theft Auto series among their influences. They sought to create a game that was distinct from Honkai Impact 3rd in terms of its quest and combat systems as well as its random events and mode of exploration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/570|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese version of the game features audio dialogue in Chinese, while the Japanese version notably features Japanese audio dialogue by many top Japanese voice artists, including Rie Tanaka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/698|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/1000|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Characters ==\nDuring the [[Tokyo Game Show]] in 2019, miHoYo released a promotional video for the Japanese voice acting in Genshin Impact. The video revealed several of the game's characters and their corresponding voice artists.\n\n'''Traveler (male)''', voiced by [[Shun Horie]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Traveler (female)''', voiced by [[Aoi Y\u016bki]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Jean''', voiced by [[Chiwa Sait\u014d]] (Japanese), the acting Grand Master of the Knights of Favonius.\n\n'''Amber''', voiced by [[Manaka Iwami]] (Japanese), a perky, straightforward girl, who is an Outrider of the Knights of Favonius. Her mastery of the glider has made her a three-time winner of the Gliding Championship in Mondstadt.\n\n'''Lisa''', voiced by [[Rie Tanaka]] (Japanese), an erudite witch much enamored with getting plenty of high-quality sleep, Lisa is the Librarian of the Knights of Favonius.\n\n'''Kaeya''', voiced by [[K\u014dsuke Toriumi]] (Japanese), Jean's most trusted aide in the organization. His quick wit and keen sense of humour has greatly endeared him to the residents of Mondstadt.\n\n'''Barbara''', voiced by [[Akari Kit\u014d]] (Japanese), the Deaconess of the Knights of Favonius and a shining starlet adored by all.\n\n'''Diluc''', voiced by [[Kensh\u014d Ono]] (Japanese), the most well-to-do man in Mondstadt, as can be deduced from his refined and graceful demeanor. At the same time, he believes fiercely in the duty to defend Mondstadt at all costs \u2014 something that makes him a ruthless and terrifying force on the battlefield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/character/mondstadt|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n'''Paimon''', voiced by [[Aoi Koga]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Venti''', voiced by [[Ayumu Murase]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Razor''', voiced by [[K\u014dki Uchiyama]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Xiangling''', voiced by [[Ari Ozawa]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Kamisato Ayaka''', voiced by [[Saori Hayami]] (Japanese)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Press ==\nmiHoYo publishes an official Genshin Impact manga series, which is hosted on sites including Crunchyroll,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/comics/manga/genshin-impact/volumes|title=Genshin Impact on Crunchyroll!|website=Crunchyroll|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Tapas<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tapas.io/series/Genshin-Impact|title=Genshin Impact {{!}} Tapas|last=Tapas|website=tapas.io|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> and Webtoon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.webtoons.com/en/challenge/genshin-impact/list?title_no=242646|title=Genshin Impact|website=www.webtoons.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> The series started in 2018, before the game itself was published.\n\nmiHoYo discussed Genshin Impact in an interview with Chinese TV station Dragon Television in January 2019. The interview was featured in the station's Primetime News program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cctv.com/2019/01/15/VIDEllNBWIsRNxHQcQESVSSf190115.shtml|title=[\u4e1c\u65b9\u65b0\u95fb]\u4ece\"\u65e0\u4eba\u95ee\u6d25\"\u5230\u5e74\u516520\u4ebf \"85\u540e\"\u521b\u4e1a\u8005\u6253\u9020\u4f18\u8d28\u56fd\u4ea7\u52a8\u6f2bIP_\u65b0\u95fb\u9891\u9053_\u592e\u89c6\u7f51(cctv.com)|website=news.cctv.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nGenshin Impact was first shown to the public in June 2019 at the Electronic Entertainment Expo in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/videos/1057341/genshin-impact-un-melange-de-tales-of-et-breath-of-the-wild.htm|title=Bande-annonce Genshin Impact : un m\u00e9lange de Tales of et Breath of the Wild - E3 2019|website=Jeuxvideo.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe first trailer for Genshin Impact was released on June 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact Announcement Trailer: The Outlander Who Caught The Wind|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lMdsrZ1otlA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe first closed beta testing for Genshin Impact commenced on June 21, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ithome.com/0/427/220.htm|title=\u300a\u5d29\u574f3\u300b\u4e4b\u540e\uff0c\u7c73\u54c8\u6e38\u65b0\u4f5c\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u5f00\u542f\u6d4b\u8bd5\u9884\u7ea6 - \u7c73\u54c8\u6e38,\u539f\u795e - IT\u4e4b\u5bb6|website=www.ithome.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nAt ChinaJoy 2019, miHoYo announced that Genshin Impact will be made available for the PlayStation 4 console in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact {{!}} Gameplay Trailer {{!}} PS4|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S1WmmsEXtyE|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nA trailer for Genshin Impact with Japanese audio was shown to audiences at the Tokyo Game Show in September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact: Come explore Teyvat with Amber! (Japanese Version)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kuLkPigM8Mg|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nMultiple language versions of the Genshin Impact website went live in September 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://genshin.mihoyo.com genshin.mihoyo.com] , official website\n\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Action role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in China]]\n[[Category:Upcoming video games scheduled for 2020]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Undisclosed paid|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| collapsible = \n| state = \n| italic title = \n| title = Genshin Impact\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| developer = miHoYo\n| publisher = \n| series = \n| engine = Unity\n| platforms = [[PlayStation 4]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = Spring 2020\n| genre = [[Action role-playing video game|Action role-playing]]\n| modes = \n| director = \n| producer = \n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = \n| writer = \n| composer = \n| cabinet = \n| arcade system = \n| cpu = \n| sound = \n| display = \n}}\n'''Genshin Impact''' is an upcoming [[open-world]] [[Action role-playing game|action role-playing video game]] developed by miHoYo. It is the second game from miHoYo to feature original IP (the first being Gun GirlZ).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mihayo.com/game.html|title=\u7c73\u54c8\u6e38-TECH OTAKUS SAVE THE WORLD|website=www.mihayo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Genshin Impact'' was announced in June 2019, with a release target of spring 2020, on both Windows and iOS - the reveal trailer showed an open world heavily inspired by ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]]'' in terms of presentation and gameplay. A [[beta test]] was to be run at the end of June.<ref>{{citation| url = https://gamerant.com/genshin-impact-game-zelda/ | title = Zelda-Inspired Open World Action Game 'Genshin Impact' Announced | first = Rory | last = Young | date = 8 June 2019 | work = gamerant.com }}</ref><ref>{{citation|  url = https://www.polygon.com/2019/6/21/18700922/genshin-impact-gameplay-beta-breath-of-the-wild-clone-botw | title = That Breath of the Wild anime \u2018clone\u2019 actually looks impressive | first = Patricia | last = Herndandez | date = 21 June 2019 | work = www.polygon.com }}</ref>\n\nAt Sony's ChinaJoy 2019 event the game was announced as also being published for [[PlayStation 4]].<ref>{{citation| url = https://gematsu.com/2019/08/genshin-impact-coming-to-ps4-in-2020 | title = Genshin Impact coming to PS4 in 2020 | first = Sal | last = Romano | date = 1 Aug 2019 | work = gematsu.com }}</ref> A [[Nintendo Switch]] version was announced on January 13, 2020 via press release.\n\n== Setting ==\nIn a world called Teyvat, certain individuals chosen by the gods are given a Vision \u2014 magical gemstones that give their bearers the ability to control an element. The player starts out as a Traveler of unknown origin who is searching for a lost sibling. The player can choose between a male or female version of the Traveler. As the adventure progresses, the player controls several other characters met by the Traveler on their journey, each with unique personalities and special abilities, as they undertake quests to understand the truth about the primordial gods of this world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\nThe game features an open-world map, which the player explores by walking, climbing, swimming and gliding as necessary. Many objects and places of significance are spread throughout the map.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gnn.gamer.com.tw/detail.php?sn=180824|title=\u300a\u5d29\u58de 3rd\u300b\u958b\u767c\u5546\u958b\u653e\u4e16\u754c\u5192\u96aa\u65b0\u4f5c\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u66dd\u5149 \u540c\u6b65\u516c\u958b\u9996\u652f\u9810\u544a\u5f71\u7247|website=\u5df4\u54c8\u59c6\u7279\u96fb\u73a9\u8cc7\u8a0a\u7ad9|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Players can control up to four of their characters at any one time. By completing quests to advance the story, the player is able to unlock a total of 30 playable characters.\n\nEach character has two unique combat skills: a normal and a special skill. The normal skill can be used at any time except for the cooldown period immediately after use, while the special skill has an energy cost, requiring the user to amass sufficient elemental energy first.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shouyou.gamersky.com/review/201906/1196056_2.shtml|title=\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u6d4b\u8bd5\u7248\u8bd5\u73a9\uff1a\u56fd\u4ea7\u624b\u6e38\u79bb3A\u6700\u8fd1\u7684\u4e00\u6b21 _ \u6e38\u6c11\u661f\u7a7a\u624b\u6e38\u9891\u9053|website=shouyou.gamersky.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Genshinimpact/|title=Genshin Impact|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nCooking is another significant aspect of Genshin Impact's gameplay. Players gather many resources in the course of their adventure, some of which can be turned into dishes via cooking. Some dishes regenerate characters' health, while others boost attack or defensive abilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shouyou.gamersky.com/review/201906/1196056_3.shtml|title=\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u6d4b\u8bd5\u7248\u8bd5\u73a9\uff1a\u56fd\u4ea7\u624b\u6e38\u79bb3A\u6700\u8fd1\u7684\u4e00\u6b21 _ \u6e38\u6c11\u661f\u7a7a\u624b\u6e38\u9891\u9053|website=shouyou.gamersky.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nmiHoYo announced work on a new project using the Unity development platform at the end of January 2017, three months after the initial release of Honkai Impact 3rd. The company stated its intention for the new project was to strengthen the company's R&D capabilities and produce higher-quality games. The project in question was Genshin Impact.\n\nThe game's developers have cited The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild and the Grand Theft Auto series among their influences. They sought to create a game that was distinct from Honkai Impact 3rd in terms of its quest and combat systems as well as its random events and mode of exploration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/570|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese version of the game features audio dialogue in Chinese, while the Japanese version notably features Japanese audio dialogue by many top Japanese voice artists, including Rie Tanaka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/698|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/1000|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Characters ==\nDuring the [[Tokyo Game Show]] in 2019, miHoYo released a promotional video for the Japanese voice acting in Genshin Impact. The video revealed several of the game's characters and their corresponding voice artists.\n\n'''Traveler (male)''', voiced by [[Shun Horie]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Traveler (female)''', voiced by [[Aoi Y\u016bki]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Jean''', voiced by [[Chiwa Sait\u014d]] (Japanese), the acting Grand Master of the Knights of Favonius.\n\n'''Amber''', voiced by [[Manaka Iwami]] (Japanese), a perky, straightforward girl, who is an Outrider of the Knights of Favonius. Her mastery of the glider has made her a three-time winner of the Gliding Championship in Mondstadt.\n\n'''Lisa''', voiced by [[Rie Tanaka]] (Japanese), an erudite witch much enamored with getting plenty of high-quality sleep, Lisa is the Librarian of the Knights of Favonius.\n\n'''Kaeya''', voiced by [[K\u014dsuke Toriumi]] (Japanese), Jean's most trusted aide in the organization. His quick wit and keen sense of humour has greatly endeared him to the residents of Mondstadt.\n\n'''Barbara''', voiced by [[Akari Kit\u014d]] (Japanese), the Deaconess of the Knights of Favonius and a shining starlet adored by all.\n\n'''Diluc''', voiced by [[Kensh\u014d Ono]] (Japanese), the most well-to-do man in Mondstadt, as can be deduced from his refined and graceful demeanor. At the same time, he believes fiercely in the duty to defend Mondstadt at all costs \u2014 something that makes him a ruthless and terrifying force on the battlefield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/character/mondstadt|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n'''Paimon''', voiced by [[Aoi Koga]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Venti''', voiced by [[Ayumu Murase]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Razor''', voiced by [[K\u014dki Uchiyama]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Xiangling''', voiced by [[Ari Ozawa]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Kamisato Ayaka''', voiced by [[Saori Hayami]] (Japanese)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Press ==\nmiHoYo publishes an official Genshin Impact manga series, which is hosted on sites including Crunchyroll,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/comics/manga/genshin-impact/volumes|title=Genshin Impact on Crunchyroll!|website=Crunchyroll|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Tapas<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tapas.io/series/Genshin-Impact|title=Genshin Impact {{!}} Tapas|last=Tapas|website=tapas.io|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> and Webtoon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.webtoons.com/en/challenge/genshin-impact/list?title_no=242646|title=Genshin Impact|website=www.webtoons.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> The series started in 2018, before the game itself was published.\n\nmiHoYo discussed Genshin Impact in an interview with Chinese TV station Dragon Television in January 2019. The interview was featured in the station's Primetime News program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cctv.com/2019/01/15/VIDEllNBWIsRNxHQcQESVSSf190115.shtml|title=[\u4e1c\u65b9\u65b0\u95fb]\u4ece\"\u65e0\u4eba\u95ee\u6d25\"\u5230\u5e74\u516520\u4ebf \"85\u540e\"\u521b\u4e1a\u8005\u6253\u9020\u4f18\u8d28\u56fd\u4ea7\u52a8\u6f2bIP_\u65b0\u95fb\u9891\u9053_\u592e\u89c6\u7f51(cctv.com)|website=news.cctv.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nGenshin Impact was first shown to the public in June 2019 at the Electronic Entertainment Expo in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/videos/1057341/genshin-impact-un-melange-de-tales-of-et-breath-of-the-wild.htm|title=Bande-annonce Genshin Impact : un m\u00e9lange de Tales of et Breath of the Wild - E3 2019|website=Jeuxvideo.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe first trailer for Genshin Impact was released on June 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact Announcement Trailer: The Outlander Who Caught The Wind|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lMdsrZ1otlA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe first closed beta testing for Genshin Impact commenced on June 21, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ithome.com/0/427/220.htm|title=\u300a\u5d29\u574f3\u300b\u4e4b\u540e\uff0c\u7c73\u54c8\u6e38\u65b0\u4f5c\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u5f00\u542f\u6d4b\u8bd5\u9884\u7ea6 - \u7c73\u54c8\u6e38,\u539f\u795e - IT\u4e4b\u5bb6|website=www.ithome.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nAt ChinaJoy 2019, miHoYo announced that Genshin Impact will be made available for the PlayStation 4 console in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact {{!}} Gameplay Trailer {{!}} PS4|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S1WmmsEXtyE|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nA trailer for Genshin Impact with Japanese audio was shown to audiences at the Tokyo Game Show in September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact: Come explore Teyvat with Amber! (Japanese Version)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kuLkPigM8Mg|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nMultiple language versions of the Genshin Impact website went live in September 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://genshin.mihoyo.com genshin.mihoyo.com] , official website\n\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Action role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\